<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vajpayee Not Invited to Form Government in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)
prime ministerial candidate A. B. Vajpayee said Thursday evening
that he had not been invited by President K. R. Narayanan to form
the next government.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee Thursday evening called on the president and submitted
documents to prove the support of 240 out of 543 MPs in the Lower
House of Parliament, telling the president that talks with
All-India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (AIADMK), which has 27
MPs, had not yielded any result so far.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen after his 40-minute meeting with the
president, Vajpayee said that the president told him that he would
consider everything and let his decision be known by day after
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee had called on the president Tuesday evening after he
received the president's letter asking him whether he would be
"able and willing" to form a "stable government" on the same day,
and claimed to be able to form a stable government.
</P>
<P>
Then the president asked him to furnish documents supporting
his claim to form a stable government and Vajpayee promised to do
so Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With his Tamil Nadu allies failing to forward their letters of
support Thursday evening, Vajpayee and other BJP leaders have been
greatly upset.
</P>
<P>
Apart from asking the BJP to dismiss the present Tamil Nadu
government, AIADMK supremo Jayalalitha has also asked the
allocation of finance and law portfolios to her nominees.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee expressed his inability to give any commitment on the
demands like dismissal of the Tamil Nadu government. He also said
Thursday evening that there was no question of succumbing to any
pressure for giving the finance portfolio to AIADMK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
