<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Visits Russia in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, praising the role played by Moscow in resolving the Iraqi
weapons inspection crisis, said on Thursday that he would visit
Russia early next month.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the National Press Club in Washington,
Annan said, the main purpose of his visit is to show that the
world community stand together to deal with the weapons inspection
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"I'll be in Moscow beginning of April, and again to show that
we all stand together on this Iraqi crisis, and send a message to
the Iraqi leadership that they've signed an agreement and the
whole international community intends to hold them to its
fulfillment," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Russia, France and China upheld a peaceful solution to the
stand-off between Iraq and the United States over the weapons
inspection crisis. Last month, a deal signed between Annan and the
Iraqi authorities averted a war.
</P>
<P>
Annan praised Russia's role in the process. "Russia played a
very important role, and right from the beginning sought a
diplomatic solution, sending a deputy foreign minister as an
envoy, and he worked very hard at getting an agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that he stayed in touch with Russian leaders
prior to his trip to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"I was also in touch with Foreign Minister Primakov and President
Yeltsin, as I were with other leaders around the world in my
preparation for the trip," said Annan.
</P>
<P>
Annan reiterated his appeal for the United States to pay the
1.3 billion U.S. dollars dues it owes to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations is, as the Iraqi crisis has showed, a
unique and irreplaceable instrument for achieving through
diplomacy what the world demands," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"A stronger United Nations can do even more for the United
States and for the rest of the world," he affirmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
