<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP/GEF Assist Africa in Combating Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U. N. Environment Program
(UNEP) and Global Environmental Facility (GEF) are assisting
African countries in combating land degradation in order to
effectively implement the International Convention to Combat
Desertification.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing held here Thursday, Ahmed
Djoghlaf, Executive Coordinator of UNEP/GEF Coordination Office,
said that the impact of desertification in Africa is particularly
acute.
</P>
<P>
It threatens the lives of millions of people and seriously
affects more than 39 percent of the total area of the continent,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
In order to implement the Nairobi Program of Action to Combat
Desertification adopted in 1997, the U.N. official pointed out,
UNEP took a leading role in designing a policy framework and
promoting a meaningful portfolio in land degradation focusing on
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Djoghlaf told reporters that the next meeting of the GEF
Executive Council to be held in New Delhi on March 30-31 would
consider a UNEP-sponsored project which is designed to address
the transboundary land degradation issues of Mauritania and
Senegal.
</P>
<P>
The project which will be implemented in five years time at a
cost of 12.3 million U.S. Dollars is aimed at addressing the root
causes of biodiversity loss from land degradation in five
critical ecosystems, covering 60,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
In July this year, he said, the GEF Executive Council will
discuss another UNEP/GEF project of 10 million Dollars to improve
the management of indigenous vegetation for the rehabilitation of
degraded rangelands in the arid zones of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The 10 million Dollars Land Management and Environmental
Change Project covering Ghana, Guinea, Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda
is designed to develop sustainable and participatory approaches
to biodiversity conservation within agricultural systems, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Seven other transboundary land degradation UNEP/GEF projects
which are estimated to cost more than 50 million Dollars and
involve 20 African countries are under active preparation, he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, UNEP/GEF will assist 10 African countries in
the preparation of their national strategies, plans or programs
for the implementation of the Convention on Biological Diversity.
</P>
<P>
UNEP/GEF will allocate 2.5 million Dollars to 12 African
countries in preparing their national country studies on
biodiversity, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
UNEP is also assisting Ethiopia, Kenya and Tanzania in
preparing a 10 million Dollars project aiming at enhancing
biodiversity conservation and sustainable utilization within the
Gregory Rift Valley Lakes and Wetlands, Djoghlaf said.
</P>
<P>
GEF is a multilateral financing mechanism created to address
climate change, the conservation and sustainable use of
biodiversity, reduction of ozone layer depletion, the protection
of international waters, and other global environmental
challenges.
</P>
<P>
GEF is mandated to provide new and additional grant and
concessional funding to eligible countries to meet the agreed
incremental costs of measures designed to achieve agreed global
environmental benefits in the areas of biological diversity,
climate change, international waters and the protection of the
ozone layer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
