<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Seeks Aid for Army Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The cash-strapped Zimbabwean
government might be forced to source for more donor funds to
finance the further downsizing of the national army.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency Thursday quoted sources in government
as saying that the government is planning to further cut down the
army to 25,000 soldiers in a bid to reduce expenditure in line
with current economic demands.
</P>
<P>
Between 1994 and 1997, the Ministry of Defense reduced the
size of the army from 51,000 soldiers to 40,000 through early
retirement.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase, the government trained retrenched soldiers
to equip them with skills to start self-help projects with the
assistance of donors.
</P>
<P>
Sources in government said since the overall public service
reform program was being funded through donor assistance, the
government might turn to donors for more funds.
</P>
<P>
"There are many donors prepared to assist the government with
such programs reducing the size of the civil service," the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The government is under pressure to cut its expenditure to
reduce the skyrocketing budget deficit and bring back
macro-economic stability needed for businesses to thrive, the
agency reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
