<HEADLINE> Indian President to Hold Talks with Congress, UF on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- President K. R. Narayanan
Thursday night decided to hold discussions with the Congress and
the United Front on the formation of the next government as the
Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the biggest party in the
just-concluded general elections, could only show the support of
240 MPs out of 539 declared seats so far.
</P>
<P>
"While the process of consultation with the BJP will continue,
the president will also hold discussions with leaders of other
political formations such as the Congress and the United Front,"
said a presidency communique issued here Thursday night after the
meeting between the president and BJP prime ministerial candidate
A. B. Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
With the support of only 240 members in the Lower House,
Vajpayee is well short of an absolute majority or even a working
majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
