<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Move Up 0.5 Pct in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. retail sales picked
up 0.5 percent in February, the Commerce Department reported here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The growth, which represents a seasonally adjusted 218.1
billion U.S. dollars, followed an even bigger increase of 1.0
percent in January. The January figure, the biggest gain in six
months, had originally been estimated as a tiny 0.1 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the first two months of this year shows that
consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of economic
output, began the year at a surprisingly healthy pace.
</P>
<P>
Some economists believe economic growth would be significantly
slower this year than last year because of adverse effects from
the Asian financial chaos. But so far the weakness is yet to be
felt as unemployment dipped in February to 4.6 percent, returning
to a 24-year low.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report Thursday, the Labor Department said that new
claims for unemployment benefits fell by 7,000 last week to
298,000, a sign of continued strength in the labor market.
</P>
<P>
The February sales report showed that consumer spending outside
the auto sector rose 0.6 percent. That followed a revised 1.3
percent surge in January, the biggest gain in almost two years.
</P>
<P>
The warm weather in most parts of the country, caused by El
Nino, spurred strong demand for Spring clothing, garden supplies
and other hardware products.
</P>
<P>
Sales at department stores and specialty stores climbed up by a
strong 1.3 percent, after even bigger gains of 2.1 percent in
January.
</P>
<P>
Sales at hardware and garden supply stores were up 2.0 percent
in February after a 3.6 percent jump in January. Demand in this
area has been helped not only by the weather but by a sharp drop
in mortgage rates that has sparked a boom in home sales.
</P>
<P>
Furniture sales dipped 0.4 percent in February, which marked
only a slight setback from a huge 3.3 percent gain in January.
</P>
<P>
Auto sales edged a slight 0.1 percent in February after a small
dip of 0.2 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
Sales at gasoline service stations were down 1.1 percent, the
biggest decline for any major category last month, reflecting a
drop in prices due to abundant supply.  
</P>
</TEXT>
