<HEADLINE> Uganda Government Considers Reducing Salary Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan government decided to
review wage policy in public services and reduce the wage gap
between top officaials and primary public servants, The New
Vision reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Apolo Nsibambi, the minister of public service, said in a
statement the decision was made when Ugandan president Yoweri
Museveni met with a team of parliament members Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president asked for reducing the gap of 30 times to 20
times between the top officials and primary public servants.
</P>
<P>
The ministers of the country earn some 1,300 u.s. dollars
while a primary worker earns some 45 u.s. dollars, local sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Sources in parliament commitees on presidential and foreign
affairs and on public affairs said the president gave the
minister a month for reviewing the presidential emoluments and
benefits bill and the overall wage structure and report to the
committees.
</P>
<P>
The president also asked for freezing pay for top officials
for four years.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed that the present wage ratio between the
highest and lowest of 1:30 should be revised.
</P>
<P>
But still, some parliamentarians reportedly told the president
during the meeting that he set a bad precedent to have little
wage as a state head. Some suggested at the meeting that if
Museveni did not want money he could donate it to charity.
</P>
<P>
Some parliamentarians asked for the increase of their salary
several times before. Wednesday's meeting was the third time the
president met the parliament members on the matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
