<HEADLINE> French Automaker Renault Earns Net Profit in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The French automaker Renault earned
5.4 plus billion francs (900 million U.S. dollars) of net profits
in 1997, during which it closed the Vilvorde assembly plant in
Belgium and laied off tens of thousands of workers, announced
Louis Schweitzer, the president of the group on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The semi-public and semi-private automobile group is apparently
recovering from years of deficits with a net loss of 5.2 plus
billion francs (870 million U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Renault plans more lay-offs this year and the Communist
unionists in the group have asked the government of
Seine-Saint-Denis, the prefecture where the headquarters of
Renault is located, to stop the plan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
