<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President to Attend IGAD Summit on Sudan, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel Arap Moi
will visit Djibouti early next week to attend a regional summit
on troubled Sudan and Somalia, a source with the Foreign Ministry
told Xinhua Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The President will be accompanied by his Foreign Minister
Bonaya Godana, said the source.
</P>
<P>
The summit of the Inter-Governmental Authority on Development
(IGAD) grouping seven eastern African and Horn of Africa states,
is scheduled to start on Monday and will last one or two days,
according to the source.
</P>
<P>
Among other regional leaders expected to attend the summit are
presidents Omar el-Bashir of Sudan, Issaias Afeworki of Eritrea
and Yoweri Museveni of Uganda and Ethiopian Premier Meles Zenawi.
</P>
<P>
They are believed to focus on a mediation bid to end the
15-year Sudanese civil war, as well as to promote national
reconciliation in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports said Mohamed Ibrahim Egal, the president
of the self-proclaimed Independent Republic of Somaliland, was
planning to attend the summit at that time.
</P>
<P>
After the Khartoum government met southern rebels under the
IGAD auspices in Nairobi October and agreed to resume talks in
April, a good regional diplomatic attempt was underway to settle
the Sudan conflict, said IGAD's Executive Secretary Tekeste
Ghebray.
</P>
<P>
He added on Wednesday that other issues at the summit will
include the IGAD budget and regional development projects for
road construction, food security and tackling cattle diseases.
</P>
<P>
On that same day, the Sudanese government urged European
nations to put pressure upon rebels in the south to accept its
offer of a ceasefire so that the humanitarian aid deliveries can
go unhindered.
</P>
<P>
Officials said Monday that Bashir had reshuffled his cabinet,
including one ex-rebel leader and two opposition figures among 12
new faces. Analysts said that the move appeared to be a political
concession to the southern rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) has been fighting
the Muslim-dominated Khartoum government since 1983 for greater
autonomy in the animist and Christian south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
