<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-tariff Barriers Retard Intra-regional Trade: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Problems currently obstructing
the movement of goods across borders, thereby retarding
intra-regional trade and economic development, are largely due to
high levels of informal trade.
</P>
<P>
This was said in an interview with the Zimbabwe News Agency on
Thursday in Harare by Danny Meyer, president of the African,
Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) National Chambers of Commerce,
Industry and Other Economic Operators.
</P>
<P>
Meyer, who attended a trade facilitation symposium in Geneva
this week, said trade problems could no longer be blamed on poor
infrastructural development or political instability only, but to
some extent on some non-tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
"It is, however, important to acknowledge the high level of
informal trade which takes place between countries. A number of
non-tariff obstacles are contributing to this," Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
Other barriers he pointed out included bureaucratic and
irrelevant customs and immigration procedures, undeveloped
facilities at and understaffing of busy border posts, inadequate
security at border posts and along major transport routes,
excessive charges, levies and fees, corruption and lack of
transparency and attitudes.
</P>
<P>
He said, "in consideration of the need to promote
inter-regional trade, the perception is often that products
manufactured abroad in developed countries must be superior to
those produced in neighboring countries."
</P>
<P>
He added solutions would have to be found to these problems
which inhibit cross border business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
