<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Call for U.N. Procurement Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries
called on the United Nations to increase procurement from
their suppliers, according to a press release from U.N. Office
of Communications and Public Information on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They made the point at a Fifth Committee (Administrative and
Budgetary) session on Wednesday to review the United Nations
administrative and financial efficiency, which focused on
procurement reform.
</P>
<P>
Speaking for the Group of 77, Indonesia's representative Cecep
Herawan said among qualified vendors, procurement preference
should be given to vendors from developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's representative Amjad Hussain Sial said current
suppliers roster is made up primarily of companies from
industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
Greater efforts should be made to broaden the roster's
geographical base, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sources said suppliers from developing countries only account
for 6.9 percent of the U.N. roster currently.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's representative Kabir complained that bidding on
procurement contracts remains limited to a few states.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that suppliers roster be made transparent and
procurement preference be given to countries that have paid their
assessed contributions to the U.N.. The idea was shared by India's
representative Rajat Saha.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the European Union and several other
European countries, Britain's representative Nicholas Thorne said
the European Union shares the concern of developing countries
about the lack of a fair share of the business opportunities on
offer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
