<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Raps French Mission to Probe Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
strongly criticized the French Parliament's fact-finding mission
that has been charged with probing the role French troops played
in the 1994 genocide, a report available here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This fact-finding mission is useless because the information
it will be looking for is already there, and they (the French)
are aware of it," Minister in President's Office, Patrick
Mazimhaka told Rwanda News Agency (RNA) in an exclusive interview
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
"This commission is just a hoax, since it will not have enough
juridical power to convoke anyone on the involvement of French
troops in the tragedy here," said Mazimhaka.
</P>
<P>
For the Rwandan authorities, this move by France is aimed at
hoodwinking international opinion in setting up such a powerless
fact-finding mission.
</P>
<P>
"If this is what they have preferred, the mission itself is
diversionary," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, former French Socialist Minister of Defense, Paul
Quiles, declared that the fact-finding mission is preparing to
come to Rwanda in the coming two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the mission is to probe the role of French
troops in the Rwandan genocide as well as that of other troops
which were present on the ground, Quiles pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Why do they want to document the involvement of other
troops?" Mazimhaka questioned, insinuating that the French should
restrict themselves to the involvement of their own troops in the
1994 bloodletting.
</P>
<P>
"This fact-finding mission will bring us back to square one,
while French scholars, independent reporters as well as human
rights activists were pretty well advanced in documenting the
involvement of France in the tragedy here," Mazimhaka furthered.
</P>
<P>
"All in all this fact-finding mission is a trivialization of
facts documented by independent researchers," Mazimhaka
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
