<HEADLINE> Shuttle Train Links S. Africa, Swaziland, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The passenger train
services of South Africa, Swaziland and Mozambique will introduce
a twice-weekly shuttle service between Durban and Maputo via
Mpaka in Swaziland on April 3.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) reported on Thursday
that the shuttle, the first of its kind for southern Africa, will
service three countries and travel across two borders in one day,
which would boost travel and tourism in the region.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican traders who bought stock in Durban, a port city of
South Africa, had also requested affordable, time-saving
transport, and research had confirmed that viability of the
service.
</P>
<P>
The current train transport from Maputo, the capital of
Mozambique to Johannesburg, the South African commercial hub, and
Durban, normally takes 50 hours. The new shuttle service would
cut the traveling time to 20 hours. 
</P>
