<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDNDR Introduces New Initiative to Prevent Seismic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Proper preventive measures can
help reduce casualties and damages caused by earthquakes, the
Geneva-based Secretariat of the International Decade (1990-2000)
for Natural Disaster Reduction (IDNDR) said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The IDNDR launched Thursday an initiative called the Risk
Assessment Tools for Diagnosis of Urban Areas Against Seismic
Disasters (RADIUS).
</P>
<P>
It aims at preparing earthquake scenarios and preventive action
plans in the selected cities and developing practical tools for
seismic risk assessment of urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Nine cities among 58 candidates have been selected for the case
studies: Addis Ababa (Ethiopia), Antofagasta (Chile), Bandung
(Indonesia), Guayaquil (Ecuador), Izmir (Turkey), Skopje
(Macedonia), Tashkent (Uzbekistan), Tijuana (Mexico), and Zigong
(China).
</P>
<P>
The Initiative also offers the possibility to share the
collected data with other cities, cities which are willing to
participate in the activities.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that about 700 shocks each year are
sufficiently strong to cause property damage, death or injury if
centered in a populated area.
</P>
<P>
A major portion of the world's earthquakes each year take place
in Asia and around the rim of the Pacific Ocean. Two thirds of the
world's population live in this area, where no part is free from
earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
RADIUS is financed by the Japanese government. In addition,
three international institutes give technical assistance to the
initiative: the International Center for Disaster-Mitigation
Engineering (INCEDE, Japan), the Bureau de Recherches Geologiques
et Minieres (BRGM, France) and GeoHazards International (GHI,
USA).
</P>
<P>
Planned RADIUS activities include training seminars in 1998 in
Japan with the participation of technical experts and government
officials respectively in the nine selected cities, visits of
regionally established advisory committees in order to provide
technical advice to the selected cities and to raise public
awareness, and an international workshop to be held in 1999 to
present the results of the initiative.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Now May Need Fewer Tanks, Says Defense Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Secretary George
Robertson said Thursday that he believes there are good reasons
for Britain to cut its tank numbers and to reduce its forces in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the Royal Institute of International Affairs on the
government-ordered Strategic Defense Review which began last year,
Robertson said Britain's potential enemies had cut their tank
numbers in recent years and technological advances meant tanks
were now more vulnerable to attack.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the threat of massive armored attack by
UK's potential enemies had been "much diminished in recent years".
</P>
<P>
"There are strong arguments why we might not need as many tanks
in the front line," Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
However, there were also a counter argument to consider in
favor of tanks, saying that Britain could not have contributed to
the Gulf War against Iraq as it did without a credible armored
capability, and that the effectiveness of United Nations forces in
Bosnia was in large part due to heavy weapons.
</P>
<P>
That's why a final decision on the issue had not been taken so
far, said Robertson.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said that there were arguments for Britain to
reduce its forces in Germany as the basing of UK forces there was
"a Cold War relic which has outlived its usefulness".  
</P>
</TEXT>
