<HEADLINE> Cook to Push New EU Initiative on Mideastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 12 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook said Thursday he is to push a new European Union (EU)
initiative on advancing the Middle East peace process during his
upcoming visit to the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with Israel Radio's reporter in London,
Cook said he will visit the region next week not only as British
foreign secretary but also in the capacity of the EU
presidency.
</P>
<P>
He said he would promote the new EU initiative by taking the
following three steps.
</P>
<P>
First, he would demand both Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) honor their respective commitments in
order to get the peace process going. Namely, Israel must carry
out "credible, urgent and substantial further redeployments" in
the West Bank, while the PNA is to make 100 percent effort to
fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, Cook said he would promise to extend the EU
financial aid to the PNA and explore how to best take advantage
of the EU funds to advance the peace process. He said the funds
should be used for specific projects that will contribute to
peace, such as the construction of Gaza airport, seaport and
industrial parks.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, Cook said he had committed the EU to intense diplomacy
so as to get the peace process moving. He said he would consult
with other European countries in order to get united backing for
this new initiative.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the EU had devised a five-point
plan for its new initiative on the Middle East peace process. It
includes a 15-20 percent Israeli handover of Area C in the West
Bank under total Israeli control, canceling the third Israeli
redeployment, a halt to Israeli settlements and its unilateral
moves especially in Jerusalem, implementation of the interim
agreements and the Memoradum of Security Understanding drawn by
the two sides under the U.S. sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
During his scheduled visit to the region, Cook is also
expected to visit Egypt, Jordan, Lebanon and Syrian. Cook said he
would also try to break the deadlock in the Lebanese and Syrian
peace tracks, which he termed as important parts of the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the recent Israeli offer to withdraw from South
Lebanon, but adding that "it is very difficult to separate the
Lebanese and Syrian tracks which must go hand in hand." He said
Syria plays an important role in restoring peace and stability in
South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Although the EU is eager to play a bigger role in the
mediation of the Middle East peace process, it is doubtful if it
could succeed in doing so because of the U.S. monopoly.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Europe, including Britain, last week,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu rejected London's
suggestion to halt settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
Many regarded Netanyahu's European visit as only an attempt to
deflect the U.S. pressure on Israel to take big steps to break
the Israeli-Palestinian stalemate following the recent Iraq
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Washington has been widely criticized for adopting double
standard in dealing with Middle East issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
