<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forex Shortage Causes Zambian Kwacha's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Zambia (BOZ)
explained Thursday that the limited supply of foreign exchange on
the local market has caused the continued devaluation of Zambian
Kwacha, according to Zambia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
In a response to Kwacha's continued devaluation, Kabinga
Pande, head of public relations of the central bank, said in a
statement released in Lusaka that though the demand for foreign
exchange has picked up since last year, the supply side has
experienced adverse external shocks.
</P>
<P>
The Kwacha has depreciated from 1,300 in mid-1997 to 1,700 per
Dollar this month and is supposed to experience a further
depreciation.
</P>
<P>
This results from the mismatch experienced in both the supply
and demand of foreign exchange, said the BOZ official.
</P>
<P>
He noted that seasonal factors such as the restocking by
business entities and remittance of dividends have increased
demand for foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Pande added that the supply side of foreign exchange on market
has also experienced adverse shocks, which have not helped meet
the increased demand.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the shocks have mainly been the result of
economic problems experienced in the Far East since last year.
</P>
<P>
The economic problems, said Pande, resulted in turn in the
reduction of the world's demand for copper, the country's major
source of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
He further stated that copper prices are reduced from 109
cents per pound in February, 1997 to 74 cents in February this
year.
</P>
<P>
Pande also refuted reports that the Kwacha is experiencing a
free fall without the intervention of the central bank.
</P>
<P>
He said that BOZ is committed to intervene in the foreign
exchange market to uphold the policy of maintaining a stable and
competitive rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
