<HEADLINE> Blair Says Northern Ireland Deal "Agonizingly Close" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Thursday an agreement on a Northern Ireland peace
settlement was "agonizingly close."
</P>
<P>
"We are agonizingly close to agreeing the framework or outline
of a settlement. We've obviously got to get the detail right too,"
Blair told Independent Television News after a meeting in Dowing
Street with Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams.
</P>
<P>
Blair also urged Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA
guerrillas, to re-join the peace process. Sinn Fein was expelled
from the peace talks last month but was allowed to return to the
negotiating table on March 9. Sinn Fein, however, said it would
not re-enter the talks until a meeting between Adams and Blair.
</P>
<P>
"I hope Sinn Fein come back to the process," Blair added.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he remained "stubbornly optimistic" that an overall
agreement could be reached by early next month.
</P>
<P>
"I'm still optimistic, maybe stubbornly optimistic, that we can
get to that deadline, provided there's the goodwill there for
people to negotiate," he said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, if reached by the parties in Northern Ireland,
would be put to referendums in Northern Ireland and the Irish
Republic on the same day in May.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting with Blair, Sinn Fein leader Adams told
reporters he wanted his party to return to the talks "as soon as
possible" but the decision was up to the leadership of the party
to make.  
</P>
</TEXT>
