<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Humans Produce and Respond to Pheromones: Findings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have shown for the
first time that humans produce and respond to pheromones,
subliminal scent messages widely used by animals to attract mates
and recognize one another.
</P>
<P>
Psychologists Kathleen Stark and Martha McClintock, of the
University of Chicago in the United States, have found that
undetectable scents from one woman can influence the menstrual
cycle of another.
</P>
<P>
Their findings were published Thursday in the British
scientific journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
The researchers took armpit secretions from women at a
particular stage of their menstrual cycles and smeared these
secretions on to the upper lips of women who were at different
stages of their cycles.
</P>
<P>
They then measured the rise and fall of the hormones and found
that those odourless chemicals could either speed up or slow down
the cycles, depending on the stage of the donors' cycles.
</P>
<P>
"These data demonstrate that humans have the potential to
communicate pheromonally," the psychologists concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
