<HEADLINE> UN Mission in Tajikistan Conducts air Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Mission
of Observers in Tajikistan (UNMOT) on Wednesday conducted air
operations using the Dushanbe airport, U.N. Spokesman Fred Eckhard
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, UNMOT carried out a helicopter
flight and was expected to get a fixed-wing aircraft to land at
Dushanbe airport on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, UNMOT announced that it was withdrawing three
United Nations teams from remote areas to their base in Dushanbe
because they were isolated due to heavy snow and avalanches, and
because the Tajik authorities were not allowing the United
Nations Mission to use the Dushanbe airport.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said the authorities of the Dushanbe airport have
finally given the "green light" for the United Nations Mission
to carry out its air operation.
</P>
<P>
Two teams had already been withdrawn using helicopters of the
Russian border forces, according the spokesman. He said that
those teams would be re-deployed as soon as the United Nations
"air assets are operating freely."  
</P>
