<HEADLINE> Sub-regional Customs to Discard Outdated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Customs chiefs from west and
central Africa have resolved to take immediate steps to discard
outdated procedures and complex documentation in the clearance of
import and export consignments in the region.
</P>
<P>
In a communique at the end of a three-day conference
Wednesday, the customs chiefs said modernization of their customs
services had become imperative so as to check delays in goods
clearance which also result in additional transaction cost.
</P>
<P>
The directors-general agreed to strive to harmonize and
streamline clearance procedures in line with the standard of the
World Customs Organization (WCO), the News Agency of Nigeria
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The delegates urged WCO to assist in organizing seminars and
workshops for members to master the valuation system of the World
Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
"The successful take-off of the WTO/WCO valuation in the
region can be further achieved through regional cooperation and
bilateral agreements," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
"Our concern is to ensure that regional interest are taken
into consideration in forging policies for the 21st century," it
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, customs administrations in the
west and central African region should articulate their positions
as a homogeneous group rather than "a linguistic enclave".
</P>
<P>
On technical assistance, the customs chiefs claimed that the
region was not benefiting enough from technical assistance
program of WCO, adding that it had been militating against the
implementation of several conventions.
</P>
<P>
They also resolved to strengthen cooperation with WCO on
checking fraud and other transnational crime.
</P>
<P>
The conference, held in the Nigerian capital Abuja, was
attended by delegates from Angola, Burkina Faso, Cote d'Ivoire,
Equatorial Guinea, Democratic Republic of Congo, Gabon, Mali,
Mauritania, Niger, Nigeria and Senegal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
