<HEADLINE> EU, Eastern European Countries to Enhance Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Government or state leaders from
the 15 European Union (EU) countries and their counterparts from
11 EU applicant central and eastern European countries agreed to
promote cooperation in various fields at Thursday's European
Conference held in London.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the final press conference after the one-day
meeting, British Prime Minister Tony Blair said that this first
ever pan-European conference was a "truly historical" moment by
bringing countries from all over Europe together.
</P>
<P>
"The whole objective of the conference is to create a stable,
secure and prosperous Europe," Blair said earlier.
</P>
<P>
The final statement issued after the meeting said:"The first
meeting of the European Conference marks the beginning of a new
era in European cooperation."
</P>
<P>
"The historical changes our generation has witnessed offer us
the chance, through the enlargement of the European Union, to
spread these benefits to the wider Europe and to entrench
stability and prosperity across our Continent," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
All the participants agreed to make joint efforts in combating
transnational organized crimes, protecting the environment,
promoting regional cooperation and coordinating foreign and
security policies.
</P>
<P>
"In these ways we shall together address common challenges. The
process, started in London, recognizes the links which bind all
our countries, and which we pledge to deepen and strengthen in the
interests of our people," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Attending the conference are heads of state or government from
the 15 EU members as well as from Bulgaria, the Czech Republic,
Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Romania, Slovenia,
Slovakia and Cyprus. 
</P>
