<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N., Iraqi Oil Experts Start First Round of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Oil experts from the United
Nations and Iraq held first round of talks here Thursday evening
to assess Iraq's capacity to produce and export crude oil under
an enhanced oil-for-food deal, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Head of the U.N. experts team, Britain's Charles Graham and
General Director for Studying and Planning Department of Iraqi Oil
Ministry Falih al-Kahyatt co-chaired the talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team, which comprises British, Dutch and Jordanian
experts in construction engineering, measurements and navigation,
arrived here Thursday afternoon. The team also includes one
Russian and one Frenchman -- two oil overseers working with United
Nations' Iraq program.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council on February 20 adopted resolution
1153 to more than double the amount of oil Iraq is allowed to sell
in six months to 5.2 billion U.S. dollars under the oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi officials informed the secretary-general during his visit
to Baghdad last month that for the time being, Iraq cannot export
more than 4 billion dollars worth of oil under the deal due to the
shortages of essential spare parts and the decline in oil prices
in world market.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, hit hard by the seven-year-old U.N. sanctions imposed
after its invasion of Kuwait, asked the U.N. to allow it to import
equipment and spare parts to repair its industry and pipelines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Voices Support to Arab Resistance to Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdul-Meguid Thursday defended the Arab resistance to Israeli
occupation of their land as fully legitimate, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The continued occupation of Lebanese and other Arab land will
only whet Arab resistance to that occupation. Such resistance was
invested with full legitimacy while that occupation lacked any,"
said Abdul-Meguid.
</P>
<P>
The AL secretary general was speaking to reporters on the
occasion of the 20th anniversary of Israel's invasion of south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the recent Israeli initiative on pulling out
from south Lebanon as a ploy to circumvent U.N. Security Council
Resolution 425 which calls for an immediate and unconditional
Israeli withdrawal from the occupied Lebanese territories.
</P>
<P>
Israel has announced that it is seeking bilateral negotiations
on an Israeli pullout from south Lebanon if Beirut guarantees the
security of Israel's northern territories. Lebanon has rejected
Israel's offer.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon in 1985 with the aim to protect its northern areas
from cross-border Lebanese guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Meguid said Israel's goal was to separate the Syrian and
Lebanese tracks in peace talks with Israel, which have been
deadlocked for nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, have held
sporadic peace talks since 1991. But the negotiations, which broke
off in early 1996, stalled over the fate of Golan Heights,
captured by Israel in 1967.
</P>
<P>
"Despite that the 1978 resolution (Resolution 425) orders its
immediate pullout from Lebanon, Israel continues to procrastinate
over implementing U.N. resolutions and continues with its almost
daily attacks on Lebanese territory and civilians," Abdul-Meguid
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks in London, Paris End Lower on Dow Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
ended mixed Thursday, with Frankfurt closing slightly higher and
London and Paris retreating from Wednesday's record closing highs
and finishing the session in the negative grounds.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 ended at 5,794.80, down 35.0 points or 0.60
percent after a five-session rally in a row, depressed by the
Dow's losses and by a strong pound which knocked the market back.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that a round of pre-budget profit-taking also
dented the stocks, with international markets offering little in
the way of support.
</P>
<P>
Falls in the Far East affected some issues, although many
traders were concerned about Wednesday's revelations over an
interest rate split among members of the Bank of England monetary
policy committee.
</P>
<P>
Banks and drug companies were the biggest fallers as
profit-taking swept through the two sectors.
</P>
<P>
German shares on the Frankfurt market, which closes before Wall
Street opens, ended trade at 4,839.60, up 6.84 points or 0.14
percent.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that share prices drifted in a directionless
market during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris closed at 3,526.57, down 12.86 points
or 0.36 percent as the market eased on the back of a weaker dollar
and as the Dow fell on rumors of a Japanese bank collapse.
</P>
<P>
But traders remained upbeat about the marekt's prospects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
