<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Air Force Pilots Flee to Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Canadian air force pilots are
fleeing in droves to high-payed private airlines and the military
hopes bonuses as much as 75,000 dollars will stop the pilot drain.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Thursday that about 300 pilots have left air force
squadrons, attracted by wages in the private sector that can be
more than double what they earn in the service.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 155 pilots left the military and the system produced
only 65 to replace them, according to Colonel Joseph Hincke,
director of air personnel for air staff headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
As a result, "we have slowed some operations down. We still do
operations, but we recognize that all the resources aren't there,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
A recent study showed that at junior levels the military pilots
make similar wages to civilian trainees of about 30,000 (21,000
USD) a year.
</P>
<P>
But the military fliers' salaries hit a peak of about 65,000
dollars while airlines are paying as much as 125,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Many of the pilots are choosing to leave the service at the age
of 32 or 33 years, after they have been fully trained and worked
in the forces for about 10 years, Hincke said.
</P>
<P>
In some cases, they have had enough of being constantly
transferred and are concerned about the quality of life for their
families, he added.
</P>
<P>
The government is "responding to the reality of the
marketplace" with the proposed payments to air force pilots,
Canadian Defense Minister Art Eggleton noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Rejects Turkish Proposals for Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Greece on Thursday rejected the
Turkish proposals for unconditional dialogue on all outstanding
issues between the two countries, saying that Ankara was unable to
see the road which leads to the restoration of transquility in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Turkish proposals which was handed to the
Greek ambassador in Ankara early Wednesday, acting Greek
government spokesman Nikos Athanasakis blamed Turkey for creating
all tension in the Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis also rejected Wednesday the
Turkish proposals including an invitation to Greek Foreign
Minister Theodoros Pangalos to visit Ankara, saying that the
proposals, as others in the past, aimed at creating impressions
rather than dealing with the substance of issues.
</P>
<P>
Athens needed a reply from the Turkish side to its positions on
a step-to-step approach, on how the problem of delineation of the
continental shelf in the Aegean was resolved, he said, adding that
if this was done, the two neighboring countries could enjoy good
relations.
</P>
<P>
Greek-Turkish relations have been strained over decades for
territorial waters, air space rights and the delineation of
continental shelf in the Aegean and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Currently, both countries have voiced their willingness to
better bilateral ties, but no substantial progress has been made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
