<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Turkey Discuss Deadlocked Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. special coordinator for
Cyprus, Thomas Miller said Thursday that he had "very
constructive" contacts with the Turkish officials on the Cyprus
issue, according to the semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Miller, who arrived here late Wednesday, has met with Turkish
State Minister for Europe and Cyprus Sukru Sina Gurel.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Cyprus is not static. My mission is to
bridge the differences and help the parties to find opportunities
which sometimes are not very visible," he told reporters after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said that under the circumstances an realistic attitude
will make the Turkish and Cypriots reach consensus on some
disputed issues.
</P>
<P>
Commenting the latest development of the island state, Miller
admitted that he is pessimistic about an imminent solution to
this thorny problem.
</P>
<P>
The self-declared parliament of the Turkish Cypriot community
in the north has announced the recognition of the so-called
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" a precondition for talks
with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot-dominated government, however, rebuffed this,
saying that its talks with the Turkish Cypriots would be of
bicommuncal nature.
</P>
<P>
Asked when U.S. presidential envoy for Cyprus Richard
Holbrooke will visit the region, Miller said that this will
depend on the development of the situation on the island.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Gurel said that his meeting with Miller was
aimed at exchanging views over the current situation of Cyprus,
adding he does not expect a concrete result.
</P>
<P>
Miller had visited Cyprus and Greece before he arrived here for
contacts with Turkish officials on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official had asked to meet Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz and Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit, but the
request was rejected.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when the Turkish
troops landed and took over the northern third of it in a wake of
an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The small island state has remained divided despite years of
backbreaking efforts by the United Nations and international
community to strive for a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash sent a
letter to Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides calling for the
establishment of a new Cyprus. But it met a cold response
from the Cypriot government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
