<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Has to Appear in Court: Judge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela would have to testify in court next Thursday on
his appointment of a commission of inquiry, the Pretoria High
Court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a brief judgement, Justice W de Villiers, the
judge, said that the president has to appear in court for the
South African Rugby Football Union (Sarfu) case, because it was a
matter of overwhelming public interest.
</P>
<P>
Mandela failed to appear in court last Monday as ordered by
the court to give evidence on the appointment of a commission to
investigate the affairs of Sarfu.
</P>
<P>
Sarfu is seeking a court order to declare Mandela's
appointment of the Browde Commission unlawful. It said that
Mandela did not apply his own judgement when appointing it.
</P>
<P>
The judge said he had paid particular attention to the
president's position as the head of state, but he decided it was
not in the interest of justice to revoke his order.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's lawyers applied Monday for the withdrawal of the
court order, saying the president's ability to exercise his
constitutional duties would be hampered if he is subjected to
cross-examination on evidence on every executive decision.
</P>
<P>
The president's office replied to Thursday's ruling by saying
that Mandela was quite happy to appear in the Pretoria High Court
next week.
</P>
<P>
Constitutional experts said if Mandela takes the stand to
testify next week, it would set a tricky precedent through which
executive decisions of the government could become subjects of
lengthy litigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
