<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's GDP Fell in October-December 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan's gross domestic product
(GDP) in the October-December period of 1997 dropped 0.2 percent
from the previous quarter, the Economic Planning Agency (EPA)
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The drop amounted to the equivalent of an annual fall of 0.7
percent, the EPA said.
</P>
<P>
The fall, which follows a 2.8 percent decrease in the
April-June quarter and a 0.8 percent growth in the July-September
period, prompted a pessimistic view that the Japanese economy in
fiscal 1997 may show the first decrease in 23 years.
</P>
<P>
The agency said it appears difficult for Japan to achieve the
government's economic growth target of 0.1 percent in fiscal 1997,
which ends this month.
</P>
<P>
Japan's GDP may trend downwards for the first time since fiscal
1974, when the GDP fell 0.5 percent, the agency said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
The EPA Vice-Minister, Shimpei Nukaya, attributed the
October-December economic drop to a serious decline in personal
consumption and housing investment.
</P>
<P>
Japan's real GDP came to an annualized 482.4 trillion yen
(about 3,768.8 billion U.S. dollars) in the October-December
period, preliminarily, the EPA said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic demand reduced the nation's GDP growth by a negative
0.8 percentage point, while external demand pushed it up by 0.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
Personal consumption, which accounts for about 60 percent of
the GDP aggregate, declined 0.9 percent from the previous quarter,
due partly to decreases in food and clothing consumption, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Housing investment also decreased 4.2 percent from the previous
quarter, posting the fourth straight quarterly drop, and public
investment fell 1.8 percent, the first decline since the first
quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, corporate capital spending, another engine of the
economy, rose 0.6 percent, following a 1.1 percent growth in the
previous term.
</P>
<P>
As for calendar 1997, external demand boosted Japan's GDP by
1.4 percent, while domestic demand reduced it by 0.5 percent, the
agency said. This was the first negative figure for domestic
demand in 23 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
