<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Vice-Minister Of Foreign Trade Says Exports Will Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The current financial turmoil in
Asia has had a limited impact on China's exports and the country
is confident of maintaining steady growth in exports, China's Vice
Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister, Shi Guangsheng, made the remark today at the
East China Export Commodity Fair in Shanghai. The event has been
held annually from March 5-14 since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Southeast Asian countries have seen shrinking market demand
because of the crisis, but they only account for eight percent of
China's trade, and there is still strong market demand in European
countries and the United States, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade will have both challenges and
opportunities in 1998, he said. Emphasis must be placed on making
deals, and Chinese exporters have already been speeding up reforms.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, China's exports and imports were worth 325 billion US
dollars, and in 1998, the country plans to do 345 billion US
dollars worth of trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
Business at the present East China fair is expected to be down
10-15 percent because the number of participants from Indonesia
and the Republic of Korea has declined drastically, Shi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
