<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Members Call For Enhanced Anti-Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Members of China's top advisory
body urge government departments and their staff to commit
themselves to building a clean and honest government and their
battle against corruption.
</P>
<P>
Members of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) have showed great
concern on the spread of corruptive practices in some areas and
departments, while voicing their appreciations of the progress
so far made in the anti-corruption drive.
</P>
<P>
The members held that the key to the success of the drive is
effective control over political power since the abuse of power
give rise to corruption.
</P>
<P>
An appropriate and rational power restriction mechanism should
be set up to increase the supervision and control functions of the
People's Congresses over power and the monitoring functions of
Party committees at all levels and greating enhancing the
democratic supervision, suggested Huang Shun, vice-chairman of the
Anhui Provincial Committee of China Democratic National
Construction Association.
</P>
<P>
Huang Weimin, vice-chairman of the Hunan Provincial Committee
of the Revolutionary Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang, urged
that the role of non-communist parties in democratic supervision
over governments and law enforcement should further be enhanced,
so should be the education among leading officials to improve
their ideological and legal awareness. He added the supervision
should also come from the media.
</P>
<P>
During the Eighth CPPCC National Committee, a proposal on the
establishment of an anti-corruption body within the Supreme
People's Procuratorate were carried out. And anti-corruption
bodies have been set up within procuratorates at all levels, which are
playing a vital role in combating against corruption.
</P>
<P>
Morover, Huang Weimin suggested that anti-corruption
regulations be enacted and issued as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
In a large sense, the success of the anti-corruption drive will
hinges on the awareness, support and participation of the masses
of people, noted Liu Ying, deputy director of the supervision
department of Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Li Lijun, deputy director of the supervision department of
Hunan province, advocated that tours overseas by officials on
public expenses should be controlled by a single department in a
a bid to stop the loopholes in the miseuse of public funds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
