<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Fund Eyes China's B-Share Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The China Index Fund, which was
started by the Commercial Union of Britain two month ago and was
the first index fund on China's B-share market, has raised 15
million US dollars on China's two bourses in Shanghai and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The news comes from Nicholas Baring, president of the British
company, who spoke at a seminar on the fund held in Shanghai
today. He told the gathering that many fund managers have been
worried about investing in Asia, but his company is confident of
China's development prospects and that a stable and prosperous
China will contribute to the recovery of other parts of Asia.
</P>
<P>
The fund tries to introduce overseas capital to aid China's
development and will provide a wide-range of opportunities for
foreign investors who are unfamiliar with China's stock market, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Index funds appeared in the United States in the early '60s and
are now popular in many Western countries.
</P>
<P>
The China Index Fund started with 13 million US dollars in
capital and raises capital from Britain and elsewhere with the
assistance of Credit Lyonnais Securities (Asia), Indosuez
W.I. Carr Securities, Newton Securities, and Shenyin Wanguo
Securities (Hong Kong). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
