<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's TRC Asks Court to Overturn ANC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) has asked the Cape Town High
Court to overturn the blanket amnesty granted to 37 top African
National Congress (ANC) officials.
</P>
<P>
TRC Deputy Chairman Alex Boraine said Friday that the truth
body is in the process of filing an application to ask the court
to direct the Amnesty Committee to reconsider its decision.
</P>
<P>
The Amnesty Committee last November granted blanket amnesty to
37 senior ANC officials, including Deputy President Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
Other members given amnesty include Defense Minister Joe
Modise, Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo, Justice Minister Dullah
Omar, Transport Minister Mac Maharaj, Tourism Minister Pallo
Jordan and ANC deputy president Jacob Zuma.
</P>
<P>
TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu said in the court papers that the
amnesty decision was invalid by virtue of at least four
irregularities, including that the amnesty was not for identified
acts.
</P>
<P>
Boraine said the TRC hoped the National Party (NP) would
withdraw its own court application to have the amnesty declared
invalid.
</P>
<P>
The NP, the largest opposition party in the country, Thursday
launched an application in the Cape Town High Court to "review
and set aside, alternatively correct" the granting of the blanket
amnesty.
</P>
<P>
The NP said ANC officials were given preferential treatments
and the amnesty was granted without going through the same
procedure as non-ANC members who sought amnesty. For example, the
ANC members' wrong doings were not disclosed, which is required
by normal procedure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
