<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing: A Year of Good Progress Since Being Raised in Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing has made fairly rapid
progresses in economic development and infrastructure construction
since it became a centrally-administered municipality a year ago,
according to deputies from the city, who are here attending the
annual session of the National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of its GNP last year reached 11.5 percent,
compared with the national average of 8.8 percent, and the average
income of local urban residents was about 5,320 yuan, 160 yuan
more than the nation's average, the deputies said.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas, farmers' average net income last year, still
below the national average, increased by 14.5 percent over the
previous year, they said.
</P>
<P>
Development conditions of Chongqing are relatively poor
compared with those of the country's other three
centrally-administered municipalities, but local people have been
encouraged to make greater efforts to build Chongqing into a new,
beautiful city, they said.
</P>
<P>
The total number of business people and travelers from other
parts of the country and from abroad who came to Chongqing to make
investment or for sight-seeing last year reached 17.25 million,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign banks, including those from Japan and Canada, have
set up branches in the city last year, and it approved 230 new
foreign-funded enterprises and actually used foreign funds
totaling 940 million US dollars during the year.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing has started to build three high-grade highways and is
prepared to build another five. And five new bridges have been
built across the Yangtze River, they said.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing faces severe challenges in the future. It has to
resettle about one billion people affected by the ongoing Three
Gorges Project and help more than 3.66 million poor farmers shake
off poverty, they said.
</P>
<P>
To invigorate state-owned enterprises suffering from losses and
help 400,000 laid-off workers is another hard task for the city in
the coming years, they said.
</P>
<P>
Local leaders and deputies from the grass-roots units expressed
determination to work hard so that Chongqing will achieve greater
progresses in years to come. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
