<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Prime Minister Tours Silicon Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin, accompanied by United States Vice President AL Gore,
toured Silicon Valley in northern California Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The visit was part of the 10th semi-annual meeting of the
so-called Gore-Chernomyrdin Commission, which was created five
years ago to improve U.S.-Russian ties.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders first visited the Lockheed Martin Missiles &AMP;
Space organization which has forged alliances with Russian
counterparts to develop state-of-art telecommunications satellites.
</P>
<P>
Gore noted at Lockheed that the commercial space industry was a
growing, 60 billion U.S. dollars a year business.
</P>
<P>
Russia and the United States were positioned to claim a lion's
share in the expanding market via cooperation, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
Besides Lockheed Martin, Boeing has launched a joint venture
with several Russian companies to create a sea-based satellite
launch facility.
</P>
<P>
After leaving Lockheed, the two leaders went to San Jose State
University where they co-chaired a U.S. West Coast-Russian Far
East regional cooperation meeting with a broad economic agenda.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin told the gathering of government officials and
business leaders that Russia is an enormous emerging market with
vast, untapped resources, and is eager to do business.
</P>
<P>
Gore and Chernomyrdin then went to the headquaters of San
Jose's Cisco Systems, where Chernomyrdin got a closed-door
briefing by business executives on how to develop a high-tech
economy.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders had several meetings in Washington on Wednesday
before heading to Silicon Valley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
