<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 16 Bodies Recovered from Landslide in Kashmir Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen bodies have been
recovered from a massive landslide Friday at Reshian in Leepa
Valley, about 50 kilometers from Muzaffarabad, capital of
Pakistan-controlled Kashmir area.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here Friday evening from Muzaffarabad said
that at least 30 people were feared dead and many others injured
as a result of the landslide.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are underway to search the other victims by the local
administration in collaboration with army personnel.
</P>
<P>
Torrent mud and rocks triggered by a landslide caused 30 houses
to cave in, leaving at least 30 people dead including 10 women,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The landslide occurred as a result of torrential rains,
dislodging a massive piece of land to bury a large part of the
village, causing loss to both lives and property.
</P>
<P>
The injured have been removed to the nearest hospitals for
first aid. A large number of local residents are also assisting in
the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities have called upon the federal government
for an immediate dispatch of relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
Estimates of loss of lives and property are difficult at this
stage but it is feared the casualties could go much higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Immediate Interests Focus of NPC, CPPCC Sessions (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The people's immediate interests
have been focused at the ongoing annual sessions of China's top
legislature and advisory body, when the economic system, and
social, economic setup are undergoing profound changes.
</P>
<P>
Deputies and members from the central leadership down to the
grassroots units have stressed that close attention should be
attached to the people's feelings and difficulties, which has a
direct impact on the future of China's reform, opening up and
modernization.
</P>
<P>
Ordinary people's concerns represent hot topics for discussion
at the previous NPC annual sessions and the National Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
and, the matters involved are more complex at this year's sessions.
</P>
<P>
Although people's overall living standards have kept improving
over recent years, some urbanites and rural residents are still
needy and have a relatively hard time, as new problems crop up in
the course of the economic restructuring that has swept such a
relatively backward country like China.
</P>
<P>
There is an inevitable rise in the number of workers laid off
by state-owned industrial enterprises, where in-depth reform has
entered the most crucial stage. The reform is a new thing anywhere
and the growing unemployment in its wake can hardly be understood
by all workers.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, all top leaders have underlined the importance of
the issue, pointing to the fact that it merits special attention
and should be tackled appropriately.
</P>
<P>
Whenever participating in panel discussions of different NPC
delegations, both Party General Secretary Jiang Zemin and Premier
Li Peng have call on government institutions at all levels,
enterprises and the the whole society to care for the laid-off
workers and provide them with the basic means to guarantee their
livelihood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Jobless Rate Drops to 8.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada's unemployment rate dropped
0.3 percentage points to 8.6 percent in February, Statistics
Canada reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The country's employment rose 82,000 in the month, mainly as a
result of a continued increase in Ontario and a rebound in Quebec
following the ice storm.
</P>
<P>
The employment gain builds on the growth of 1997, leaving
employment up 448,000 over the last 12 month, the statistics
agency said.
</P>
<P>
In February, full-time employment rose by 84,000, continuing
the surge that began a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In the last 12 months, full-time employment has risen 4.2
percent to 472,000, while part-time employment has fallen slightly.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that nearly half of February's employment
increase went to Canadian youths 15 to 24 years of age, the first
major increase in six months.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the youth unemployment rate dropped to 15.5
percent from 16.5 percent in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's External Trade Down in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The value of Hong Kong's
general external trade went down in January from the same month
of last year, the Census and Statistics Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the department's preliminary statistics, the
re-exports decreased by 2.9 percent over a year earlier to 99.1
billion Hong Kong dollars (12.71 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The value of domestic exports fell by 11 percent to 15.3
billion Hong Kong dollars (1.96 billion U.S. dollars), while that
of imports decreased by 14 percent to 113.2 billion Hong Kong
dollars (14.51 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Experts here attributed the fall in Hong Kong's external trade
mainly to the recent financial turmoil sweeping almost all major
economies in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
However, the department also said the external trade figures
usually display greater volatility in the first two months of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year decline in the value of both exports and
imports in January 1998 were likely to have been caused by the
different timing of the Lunar New Year holidays in 1997 and 1998,
it said, adding that it should be more meaningful to make
comparisons based on figures for January and February 1998
combined, when the figures for February are available towards the
end of this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Blasts Norway's Expulsion of Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry
issued a statement Friday expressing incomprehension and worry
over Norway's decision to expel two Russian diplomats, and declare
three other Russians persona non grata.
</P>
<P>
The ITAR-TASS news agency said the statement declared that
Oslo's decision ran counter to the principle of mutual
understanding and constructive cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Russia felt gravely sorry that Norwegian Prime Minister Kjell
Magne Bondevik postponed his planned visit to Moscow because of
the incident, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Moscow reserved the right to take measures over Norwegian
diplomats in Russia in response, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Norway accused the two Russian diplomats -- Russian embassy
attache Valery Kotsharev and advisor Yevgeny Serebriakov -- and
three former Russian diplomats of attempting, "for several years,"
to recruit Norwegians to work for Russian intelligence services.
</P>
</TEXT>
