<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Ousts Sweden in Sledge Hockey Semifinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada edged out defending champion
Sweden 2-1 in the semifinals of the ice sledge hockey at the
Winter Paralympic Games in Nagano, Japan, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Canadian goalkeeper Pierre Pichette stopped 44 shots from
Sweden which outshot the Canadians 45-11. Captain-defenseman Todd
Nicholson and forward Herve Lord scored for the winning.
</P>
<P>
In the final Saturday, Canada is to play Norway, a 4-1 winner
over Estonia in the other semifinal match.
</P>
<P>
Sit-ski racer Masahiro Shitaka of Japan claimed the men's
slalom title and became the first male Japanese to win a gold
medal in Alpine skiing after Kuniko Obinata won the first
Paralympics gold for Japan in the women's downhill.
</P>
<P>
In other categories, Rolf Heinzmann of Switzerland wrapped up
his fourth gold medal on the slopes of Shiga Kogen, sweeping all
four events for athletes with disabilities in one arm.
</P>
<P>
Hans Burn from Switzerland, captured his third gold medal with
a victory in a class for athletes with less severe disabilities in
one leg.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's Mathew Butson also clinched his third gold medal
of the games, triumphing in a category for skiers with
disabilities in one arm and one leg.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
