<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Medium-of-Instruction Policy Remains Unchanged: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The medium-of-instruction
policy of the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) remains unchanged, a senior official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Secretary for Education and
Manpower Joseph W. P. Wong reiterated the need to promote
mother-tongue teaching to enhance students' cognitive development
and learning ability.
</P>
<P>
The government has accepted the findings of the independent
Appeal Committee on appeals cases relating to the use of English
as a medium of instruction (MOI) in a number of secondary schools
from the 1998-1999 school year onwards, according to Wong.
</P>
<P>
The committee has found that of the 20 appealing schools, 14
should be allowed to continue using English as the medium of
learning, while for the other six schools, Chinese would be their
most effective MOI.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the government's MOI policy remained unchanged,
Wong outlined the objectives of the policy:
</P>
<P>
-- To strengthen the teaching and learning of Chinese and
English to enable students to be biliterate and trilingual (or be
conversant with written Chinese and English and be able to speak
fluent Cantonese, Putonghua and English);
</P>
<P>
-- To promote mother-tongue teaching to enhance students'
cognitive development and learning ability;
</P>
<P>
-- To discourage the use of mixed code (or a mixture of Chinese
and English, in teaching and learning).
</P>
<P>
An appropriate medium of instruction is crucial to a student's
effective learning, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out: "Research worldwide and in Hong Kong has shown
that students generally learn better through their mother-tongue.
They will be able to understand better what is taught, analyze
problems, express views, develop an inquisitive mind and cultivate
critical thinking."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the Quality Education Fund of the SAR
planned to set up a quality school award scheme to promote
excellence in various domains of education, with a view to
nurturing students with all-round abilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
