<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Railway a Boon for Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Resources-rich but less-developed
southwest China will be an attractive area for foreign investment
with the opening to traffic of the Nanning-Kunming Railway that
links Guangxi, Guizhou and Yunnan in southern and southwestern
China, according to deputies to the National People's Congress, in
session here since early March.
</P>
<P>
Numberous production bases and projects involving grain, coal,
aluminium, building materials and fruit are being built in
southwest China and the Beibu Gulf area in Guangxi -- all to be
served by the Nanning-Kunming Railway, according to the deputies.
</P>
<P>
Cen Hongping, secretary of Beihai Municipal Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), said that his city has signed
30-plus contracts with investors from the United States, Australia
and some other countries and regions, involving a total investment
of 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
A US-funded project, costing 900 million yuan, has started
trial operation. Work on the terminal building at Beihai Airport
invested by Siemens Co. of Germany will begin next month, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The port city of Qinzhou had 13 projects involving foreign
investment in the latter half of 1997 with a total investment of
625 million yuan, said Qinzhou acting mayor Yang Caishou, an NPC
deputy.
</P>
<P>
An aluminium production base, believed to be the largest of its
kind in China, is being built in Guangxi with advanced technology
imported from 17 countries.
</P>
<P>
Southwest China is rich in 28 mineral resources such as coal,
iron, tin and zinc. The Nanning-Kunming Railway has a designed
annual hauling capacity of 20 million tons, outstripping the
combined marine transport capacity of Beihai, Qinzhou and
Fangcheng ports by 11 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
