<HEADLINE> India's Congress Party to Consider Staking Claim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Congress party leader Sitaram
Kesri called on President K. R. Narayanan Friday night and told
him that his party would consider staking claim to form government
after consultations with party leaders, its allies and other
parties including the United Front.
</P>
<P>
The process of consultation was already on and until the party
was completely ready it would not stake its claim, he told newsmen
after his 30-minute meeting with the president.
</P>
<P>
The Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) prime ministerial candidate A.
B. Vajpayee called on the president Thursday and furnished to him
a letter with documents showing the support of 240 out of the 539
elected MPs in the Lower House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
"While the process of consultation with the BJP will continue,
the president will also hold discussions with leaders of other
political formations such as the Congress and the United Front,"
said a presidency communique issued here Thursday evening after
the meeting between the president and Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
In his Tuesday letter to Vajpayee, whose party emerged the
largest political party in the just concluded general elections,
the president asked him whether he was able and willing to form a
stable government. Vajpayee gave a positive response.
</P>
<P>
Then the president asked him to furnish documents supporting
his claim to form the next government, he promised to do so the
next day.
</P>
<P>
Yet Vajpayee could only get the support of 240 MPs instead of
252 as he said earlier after failing to receive support from its
allies in Tamil Nadu.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the United Front are also expected to call on the
president Friday evening on the formation of the government as the
president has invited leaders of Congress, the United Front and
Left parties for consultations separately Friday evening following
the BJP furnishing documents claiming support of only 249 MPs
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The impasse in government formation created by the delay of the
BJP's Tamil Nadu allies in handing over their letters of support
to the BJP continued Friday.
</P>
<P>
BJP Secretary General Venkaiah Naidu said Friday evening that
the BJP and its allies would review the latest situation Saturday.
The BJP, being the largest bloc in Parliament, should form the
government otherwise the country would have to go for another
election, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
