<HEADLINE> China to Guard Financial Crisis with Better Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior legislator said today
that China will strengthen legislation aimed at standardizing
economic activities to guard against financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"China will earnestly draw on the lessons of the financial
disturbance in southeast Asia and guard against financial crisis
through legislation," said Hu Kangsheng, deputy-director of the
Commission of Legislative Affairs under the National People's
Congress (NPC) Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The NPC and its Standing Committee have been giving priority to
safeguarding a sound operation of commercial banks and financial
institutions, maintaining financial order and preventing financial
crisis, Hu said at a press conference held during the First
Session of the Ninth NPC.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the Eighth NPC and its Standing
Committee enacted 118 laws and law-related decisions, the majority
of which are aimed at regulating economic activities.
</P>
<P>
In particular, five key laws and one decision on economic
affairs were enacted in 1995. They are Law on the People's Bank of
China, Law on Commercial Banks, Law on Insurance, Law on
Negotiable Instruments, Guarantee Law and Decision on Punishing
Crimes Disrupting Financial Order.
</P>
<P>
Draft laws on securities and trust are under deliberation in
China's top legislature, and laws concerning futures trading and
the management of investment funds have been put on the
legislative agenda, according to Hu Kangsheng.  
</P>
</TEXT>
