<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Closes Another Vietnamese Refugee Departure Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong authorities
closed another Vietnamese refugee departure center Friday, taking
a further step towards the end of the whole Vietnamese boat people
saga, a local government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this was another major step following the closure
of the Kai Tak Vietnamese Migrant Transit Center in March last
year, the Whitehead Vietnamese Migrants Detention Center in June
1997, and the North Camp of the High Island Detention Center in
January 1998.
</P>
<P>
The newly-closed center, or the New Horizons Vietnamese Refugee
 Departure Center, located at Kwun Tong Road, Kowloon, had about
270 Vietnamese illegal immigrants before the closure.
</P>
<P>
They have all been transferred to the Pillar Point Vietnamese
Refugee Center in the "New Territories," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1975, over 200,000 Vietnamese had arrived in Hong Kong,
according to the local authorities. The migrant population reached
a historical peak in October 1991, with over 64,300 Vietnamese
people accommodated in 14 camps in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With the continued efforts of all the concerned parties, the
present Vietnamese population in Hong Kong has dropped to about
1,200 Vietnamese refugees, 660 Vietnamese migrants and 980
Vietnamese illegal immigrants, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He stated: "The government (of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region) will continue with its efforts to draw the
Vietnamese boat people issue to a complete and satisfactory
conclusion." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
