<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Communist Party in Nepal Elects Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The breakaway party from the
Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) has
elected its leadership and central committee.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) said
here Friday that at its three-day meeting which concluded Friday,
a 35-member central committee has been elected and Sahana Pradhan
elected the new party's chairwoman, while former deputy prime
minister Bam Dev Gautam holds the powerful post of general
secretary.
</P>
<P>
Forty-six of the 101 MPs of the CPN-UML registered a new party
called CPN-ML on March 5 at the Parliament Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Under Nepal's law, 40 percent members of a parliamentary party
or the party's central committee can form a new party and get
recognition.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament Secretariat recognized the CPN-ML on March 6 as
a new parliamentary party, and Gautam was unanimously elected its
leader the next day.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here Friday, Gautam accused the
CPN-UML of abandoning the People's Multiparty Democracy propounded
by the late general secretary Madan Bhandari.
</P>
<P>
He said investigation into the death of Bhandari should be
continued.
</P>
<P>
Bhandari and his colleague died in May 1993 when the jeep they
were riding fell into a river, but the driver survived. The
accident remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
Gautam said his party can join hands with the Nepali Congress
(NC) on the matter of democracy.
</P>
<P>
The ruling NC now replaces the CPN-UML as the largest party in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Gautam stressed that the Indian army should be removed from
Kalapani in western Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The status of Kalapani is a decades-old issue between Nepal and
India.
</P>
<P>
Gautam also said the Mahakali Integrated Development Treaty
signed between Nepal and India is against the national interest of
Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Differences over the Mahakali treaty and other issues between
Gautam and Madhav Kumar Nepal, general secretary of the CPN-UML,
led to the split of the party, which came less than two months
after the party held its sixth national congress.
</P>
<P>
The ruling National Democratic Party (RPP), the third largest
in the country, is also split. But the Election Commission has not
recognized the splinter group led by former prime minister
Lokendra Bahadur Chand as a national party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
