<HEADLINE> Israel Not to Yield to EU Pressure: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Cabinet Secretary
Danny Naveh indicated Friday that Israel will not cave in to the
pressure from the European Union (EU) to accelerate the peace
talks with the Palestinians and harm its national security
interests.
</P>
<P>
Naveh told Israel Radio that the proposals on the peace
process, which were put forward by the EU Chairman Robin Cook,
are doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
Cook, Foreign Secretary of the EU rotating presidency country
Britain, declared early this week that the stalled peace talks
require increasing pressure for a positive response from Israel.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed his six-point plan to break the stalemate
in the peace process, which calls Israel to make "substantial,
credible and urgent further redeployment" in the West Bank and
halt "all expansion of settlements."
</P>
<P>
Naveh warned that European officials, who demand a place
for the EU alongside the United States in the process, not
to try to "impose their ideas on Israel", which may compromise
Israel's security interests.
</P>
<P>
However, Naveh agreed that the EU has an important role
to play in advancing the peace process, noting that it could
encourage the Palestinians to reach agreements with Israel on
issues, such as the opening of Gaza airport and Karni
industrial zone.
</P>
<P>
Since Britain held the EU presidency this January, it has
put the first priority of its foreign policy on advancing the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Following Cook's visit to six Middle East countries next
week, British Prime Minister Tony Blair will also tour the
region next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
