<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Majority of Shanghai Parents Want Their Children To Go to College </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A study in the city of Shanghai
has found that 85 percent of the parents living there hope their
children will be able to study at university or college.
</P>
<P>
This is in sharp contrast to the 10 percent of parents who said
they'd be happy if their children just made it through secondary
or technical school.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's Minhang District Education Bureau did the study
among 1,306 families. About 16 percent of the parents were
graduates of polytechnic schools or universities, and 47 percent
of them had a primary or junior middle school education.
</P>
<P>
Of the 72 percent of the parents who are laborers, farmers, or
clerks, less than 2 percent say they would like their children to
be farmers or laborers, and 78 percent say they would like them to
become scientists or government office workers.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that most parents spend a large amount
of money and expend a great deal of effort to provide better
conditions for their children's studies, and 10 percent have
bought computers for their children and 50 percent plan to by
computers in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
