<HEADLINE> Strobl Wins final, Schifferer Takes overall Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVE, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Josef Strobl of Austria claimed
his first World Cup downhill victory of the season in the final
race in Crans Montana, Switzerland, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
However Strobl's countryman Andreas Schifferer had already
claimed the downhill World Cup title before the finals in Crans
Montana though he finished just in 11th place Friday.
</P>
<P>
Strobl, who was third in downhills for twice this season, won
the shortened World Cup finals race with a time of one minute
30.84 seconds.
</P>
<P>
It was Strobl's fifth victory in his career as his last
downhill win was in Val d'Isere, 1995, but he won the season's
opening parallel slalom in Tignes, France.
</P>
<P>
Didier Cuche of Switzerland came as second.
</P>
<P>
Hermann Maier of Austria, double Olympic gold medallist who did
not compete in Friday's race for back problems, was funner-up in
the overall standings, 10 points ahead of France's Nicolas Burtin.
</P>
<P>
The race was originally scheduled for Thursday but was called
off due to fog. It finally went ahead after a further two more
hour delay because of more bad weather.  
</P>
</TEXT>
