<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Silk Road Makes A Smaller World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- For a long time, the Silk Road
meant nothing but a hazy memory of the distant past of commercial
and cultural exchanges between East and West.
</P>
<P>
But, on December 1, 1992, the Silk Road was restored of its
former glory, when a train pulled out of the station at
Lianyungang, a port on the east coast of China, for Rotterdam in
the Netherlands, and for the past five years the Silk Road has
had a new name, the Second Eurasian Continental Bridge.
</P>
<P>
The new 10,900-km land bridge passes through Siberia and snakes
its way across a dozen countries on two continents. And because it
is more significant for China than perhaps for any other country,
the Chinese government has spent billions of yuan on
infrastructure for it.
</P>
<P>
Lianyungang, in Jiangsu Province, is being turned into a large
international hub with 25 berths and a yearly capacity of 19.95
million tons of goods, and a plan to add a hundred more, each with
a 10,000-ton or greater capacity to meet future needs.
</P>
<P>
Railways have been improved for the 4,131-km Chinese section of
the new bridge, from Lianyungang to the Altay Pass in the Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the cargo capacity of the land bridge
has doubled annually, and in 1997, Lianyungang handled 30,016
TEUs. Chinese officials say that goods headed west accounted for
most of the goods shipped over the new land bridge in the first
two years, but now the ratio of east-west and west-east goods is
about 50-50.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan, Germany, and Hong Kong, have joined a
dozen other countries and regions in using the route for faster
shipment of goods, and local experts and scholars see a bright
future for the bridge, which links the Pacific with the Atlantic
and paves the way for prosperity in the Asian Pacific Region and
economic cooperation between Europe and Asia, according to Tong
Dalin, a prominent Chinese economist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
