<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Book Describes World's Scientific Developments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A book from the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS) now gives readers a good picture of the world's
scientific developments in common language.
</P>
<P>
The "Reports on Scientific Developments" will be out soon and
will introduce people to the most advanced scientific ideas and
the latest developments and improve scientific awareness,
according to Lu Yongxiang, president of CAS.
</P>
<P>
In the preface to the book, Lu says that China should try to
follow a strategy of invigorating itself through science and
technology and sustainable development in next century.
</P>
<P>
Nobel Prize winner Prof. Lee Tsung-dao has contributed an
article on developments in physics in the 21st century, and
Shing-tung Yau, a CAS academic, wrote about developments in
mathematics in China.
</P>
<P>
CAS will publish similar books every two years, and an abridged
version will be published every year. Scholars say the book is
easy to read, even for ordinary people, and is also worth having
as a scientific reference book. 
</P>
</TEXT>
