<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nomination for Subsector Elections Begins in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Relevant returning officers in
Hong Kong began to accept candidates nomination on Friday for the
Election Committee subsector elections to be held on April 2.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Legislative Council elections will include the
subsector elections, which will return a total of 683 members of
the Election Committee, and the general election of the
Legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) on May 24.
</P>
<P>
These 683 members, together with the ex-officio members
including Hong Kong deputies to the National People's Congress
and Provisional Legislative Council members, as well as religious
subsector, will form an 800-strong Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
According to the government guidelines on election-related
activities in respect of the 1998 Legislative Council elections, a
candidate of an Election Committee subsector must be subscribed by
not less than five registered voters and each voter may only
subscribe as many nominations regarding a particular subsector as
10.
</P>
<P>
Nomination forms must be handed in to the relevant returning
officer in person during the nomination period which will last up
to March 20.
</P>
<P>
Under the Basic Law, the SAR's first Legislative Council shall
be composed of 60 members, with 20 returned by geographical
constituencies through direct elections, 10 by the Election
Committee and 30 by functional constituencies.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the SAR government also published the 1998 final
registers of voters and electors for the Election Committee
subsector elections and the Legislative Council election.
</P>
<P>
The geographical constituencies' register shows that the size
of the electorate now stands at 2.795 million, which represents an
increase of 264,000 from 2.531 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"That means about 70 percent of the potential electors may go
to the polls on May 24," a spokesman for the Registration and
Electoral Office said.
</P>
<P>
The electorate of the 28 functional constituencies totals
138,984, representing about 60 percent of the potential electors.
</P>
<P>
As for the 35 Election Committee subsectors, more than 143,000
voters have been registered. This represents a registration rate
of about 59 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
