<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> b u p 2553 China-NPC-Scientific Innovation Innovations of Science, Technology Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists today called
for taking effective measures to encourage innovations in science
and technology to ensure a steady growth of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"Weak competitiveness in science and technology constitutes a
potential risk for China's economic development in the coming
century," said Wang Xuan, an academician from the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS) and a deputy to the Ninth National People's
Congress, in session here since early March.
</P>
<P>
Wang, also inventor of the Chinese-character computerized
typesetting system which is widely used around the world, said
that, according to a latest report released by the CAS, China's
competitiveness in science and technology has declined for three
years running.
</P>
<P>
At present, national total investment in research and
development only accounts for 0.5 percent of the country's GNP,
Wang said, adding that, in terms of patents filed and progresses
made in basic sciences, China lags behind many other countries.
</P>
<P>
China's high-tech sector contributes to less than 10 percent of
the country's economic growth, compared with 50 percent or so in
developed countries, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Insufficient input in science and technology, as well as
problems in the old science management system, are impeding
scientific progress in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Only when the nation's high-tech sector has developed can it
meet challenges of the next century," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Chen Zhangliang, vice-president of Beijing University and also
an NPC deputy, said that China has numerous scientific
institutions, which do not produce many research results, nor have
many of such results commercialized. "This is closely related to
the existing science management system," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Luo Yifeng, an expert in high-tech fibers, noted that China has
to be ready for challenges from a fast developing information
economy, in which any economic increases will rely on innovations
and accumulations of knowledge
</P>
<P>
"Chinese enterprises should set up their own information
system, and research institutions should provide them with
innovations," Luo said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is already paying close attention to the
issue, and various measures are being taken, Luo said, quoting
Premier Li Peng as saying that special attention will be paid to
quickening the development of the high-tech industry and promoting
the integration of science and technology with economic
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
