<HEADLINE> Sino-Australian Agreement For Alternative Fuel Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Three Australian companies will
cooperate with Tianjin, the largest port city in north China, in
building a power plant that uses waste as fuel.
</P>
<P>
The Environmental Power Co. Ltd., Great Pacific Financial
Group, and Prosperous Corp. Ltd. will put 45 million US dollars
into the project and the Tianjin Environmental Engineering Design
Institute will provide 1,200 tons of garbage per day for the
plant, according to an agreement signed here recently.
</P>
<P>
The plant will be built on six ha of land and will be able to
handle about a fifth of the city's total amount of garbage. It
will be transferred to the Chinese partner after 30 years of
operation. It is expected to recover all its investment within 20
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
