<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Croatia Vow to Enhance Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Croatia announced
Friday in a joint statement that they are determined to further
strengthen cooperation in political, economic and cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
The document faxed to Xinhua was issued at the end of the
official visit to Turkey by Croatian Deputy Prime Minister and
Foreign Minister Mate Granic.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the capital Ankara, Granic met with Turkish
President Suleyman Demirel, Parliament Speaker Hikmet Cetin and
Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Granic and his Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem exchanged views
over bilateral and international issues of common concern and also
signed a memorandum of understanding on cooperation between the
foreign service trading centers of the two ministries.
</P>
<P>
"The two ministers agreed to continue their political
consultations between themselves as well as between the
high-ranking officials of their respective ministries on a regular
basis," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
They also stressed that there is a great potential to exploit
between the two countries in the fields of trade and economic
cooperation, it added.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers said that cultural relations between
Turkey and Croatia should also be promoted through great efforts.
</P>
<P>
As to regional issues, Granic and Cem discussed the violences
in the Kosovo province of the Yugoslavian Federation, expressing
their deep concern about the grave situation there.
</P>
<P>
"They strongly and unreservedly condemned the terrorist actions
to achieve political goals as well as suppression of peaceful
demonstrations with violence," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
They called on the parties concerned to find a solution to the
crisis through social dialogues within the framework of
maintaining the territorial integrity of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Granic paid a two-day visit to Turkey on March 12 and
13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
