<HEADLINE> S'pore Police Nab 350 Illegal Immigrants in Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Singapore police caught nearly
350 suspected illegal immigrants and overstayers in an island-wide
operation, Singapore television reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ten-hour operation, which started last night, involved
police from all seven land divisions. And for the first time,
local media was allowed to come along to capture the action.
</P>
<P>
In one such raid, more than 80 officers from the Ang Mo Kio
Division in the central part of Singapore rounded up more than 100
suspects in the northern area, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that of the 350 caught, 48 were for overstaying and the
rest were suspected to be illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
During the operation, targets included coffee shops, lodging
houses, construction sites and even provision shops, the
television report said.
</P>
<P>
The police was quoted as saying that they aimed to hit places
where suspected illegals were known to congregate, work or stay.
</P>
<P>
Those who were caught without valid identification papers were
arrested and hauled back for questioning. They included nationals
from Indonesia, Thailand, India, and Bangladesh, the television
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
