<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Records Improved Air Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Beijing weekly air quality report
showed an improvement last week, with pollution levels falling
from medium to slight.
</P>
<P>
The city's air pollution index for the period between March
6-12 stood at 188, a ranking indicative of a slight pollution
level.
</P>
<P>
However, the report indicated lingering major pollutants such
as nitrogen and oxygen compounds.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has released its weekly air quality report since
February 28 to inform residents of environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
The first report indicated a level of 206 with the second
report showing a slight drop to 203, figures indicating medium
pollution.
</P>
<P>
China's National Environmental Protection Agency (NEPA)
classifies air quality in five grades, with an index of under 50
representing good environmental conditions. Relatively good
conditions fall between 50-100; slight levels between 101-200,
medium levels between 201-300 and serious pollution over 300.
</P>
<P>
"The use of coal and motor vehicle emissions are the major
factors causing pollution in Beijing," according to Zhao Yixin,
director of the Beijing Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The city ranks first on the list of world capitals with an
annual coal consumption of 28 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In addition, statistics show that the city has over 1.2 million
motor vehicles, up three-fold on only ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
Municipal authorities plan to extend great efforts to improve
the air quality over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
China has a total of 33 cities which currently release weekly
air quality reports, including Nanjing, Shanghai, Dalian, Xiamen
and Lanzhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Innovation System to Center on Academy of Sciences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS) will be a key component in the state innovation system to be
established by the year 2010, according to CAS President Lu
Yongxiang.
</P>
<P>
Lu made the remarks today during a meeting held to commemorate
the 20th anniversary of the national science conference regarded
as the milestone in development of the nation's science and
technology sectors.
</P>
<P>
The system will consist of national scientific innovation and
technological projects and an education plan designed to
coordinate a knowledge-based economy for the 21st century,
according to a CAS report initially approved by central
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The scientific innovation project, which will involve CAS and a
number of major scientific institutes, will help China gain a
tenth place world ranking in terms of scientific competitive power by
the year 2010, according to the report. China ranked 28th in the
world in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The capacity to access innovative scientific knowledge will be
crucial to the nation's future," said Lu, adding that "CAS, the
leading scientific organization in China, will take the lead in
implementing the knowledge-based scientific innovation
project." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
