<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Suffers Drought in North, Floods in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China is suffering from
abnormally high flood waters in the south while the north battles
a severe drought, said Niu Maosheng, minister of water resources.
</P>
<P>
Since last October southern China has had more rain than usual,
causing floods in the provinces of Jiangxi, Hunan, Jiangsu,
Zhejiang, Fujian and Guizhou. These provinces' flood-control
headquarters have been monitoring the situation around the clock
and preparing for an intense period of flood-watching, he said.
</P>
<P>
The majority of northern China, on the other hand, received
20-to-90 percent less moisture, Niu said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of February, 3.96 million hectares of farmland have
been affected by drought. The lower reaches of the Yellow River
ran dry much earlier than last year.
</P>
<P>
Niu said that the worst drought is yet to come, probably in
May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
