<HEADLINE> Uganda Launches Special Syllabus for Nomads in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Northeast
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Uganda launched a special
syllabus for Karamajon, a tribe in the remote northeast of the
country, reported "The Monitor" Friday.
</P>
<P>
Amanya Mushega, education minister, launched the scheme on
local language in its lower primary schools on Thursday#,saying
the move is not an isolated one.
</P>
<P>
It is part of the country's universal primary education (UPE)
program which provides free education for every four children for
a family, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
The syllabus for Karamajon, a result of consultations between
the Education Ministry and elders and youth of Karamajon tribe,
suggests for a three-hour study from 07:00 to 10:00 a.m. to fit
in with the nomadic lifestyle of Karamajon, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the custom of Karamajon, the boys should pasture
their cattle and the girls have obligation to tend crops.
</P>
<P>
Peter Lokeris, the presidential adviser on Karamajan affairs,
noted that the area of Karamajan is delayed with development and
suffers from illiteracy. Their enrolment rate of children into
schools is only 20 to 25 percent, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
