<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Policy Bank Announces Quarterly Lending Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The State Development Bank (SDB),
a major policy-oriented bank, plans to extend loans totalling 12.2
billion yuan (1.47 billion US dollars) during the first quarter of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Loans totalling 12 billion yuan will go for capital
construction and 200 million yuan for technical upgrading. The
loans will benefit more than 200 projects, including the Shuohuang
Railway (from Shuozhou in north China's Shanxi Province to
Huanghua in neighboring Hebei Province), a new section of the
Beijing Subway System, the Pudong Airport in Shanghai, the Ertan
Power Station and the Wanjiazhai Water Conservancy Project.
</P>
<P>
The government has granted the SDB approval to issue a total of
95 billion yuan in loans during 1998.
</P>
<P>
SDB President Yao Zhenyan said the bank will place priority on
loans to basic industries, infrastructure projects, central and
western regions, projects in new economic growth areas, large
enterprises and enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
No loans will be extended to ordinary small projects, luxury
real estate development, commercial projects and projects prone to
inefficiency, according to Yao.
</P>
<P>
Late last year, the People's Bank of China (PBOC), the nation's
central bank, announced the credit quota system for state-owned
commercial banks would be abolished at the beginning of 1998. The
PBOC also replaced mandatory lending plans with guiding
plans.
</P>
<P>
However, the decision does not affect policy-oriented banks,
and related institutions will continue to extend loans in
accordance with mandated government plans.
</P>
<P>
SDB, founded in 1994 to finance the country's major
construction projects, extended loans totalling 107.7 billion yuan
in 1997, with 95.5 percent of related funds going for medium- to
large-sized projects and technical renovations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
