<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Reduces Spindles as Part of Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, China's fourth
municipality, has joined the nationwide campaign to destroy
spindles as part of the effort to restructure the textile industry.
</P>
<P>
Local sources reported that the No.1 Cotton Mill destroyed
obsolete spindles on Thursday to mark the beginning of Chongqing's
effort to revamp its loss-making textile sector.
</P>
<P>
Primary products such as yarn and cloth account for 70 percent
of the city's textile output, with local sources noting that the
city is not a cotton producer. The government plan calls for
Chongqing to eliminate at least 40 percent of some 497,000
obsolete spindles, substantially more than the national average of
25.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The textile industry's high asset-to-liability ratio stands at
119 percent, with the vast majority of enterprises in the sector
operating in red. The situation prompted the city government
decision to eliminate 150,000 cotton spindles over the next three
years, with plans calling for the elimination of 133,400 spindles
during 1998.
</P>
<P>
The China Huacheng Group, a profitable venture with total
assets of 22.9 billion yuan, recently signed an agreement to merge
four of the city's cotton mills, including the No.1 Mill.
</P>
<P>
The merger will involve assets totalling 840 million yuan,
156,000 spindles, a work force of 15,000 and 7,300 retirees.
</P>
<P>
China plans to eliminate 10 million spindles and reduce the
industry's work force by some 1.2 million people over the next
three years. Shanghai's ongoing effort has already resulted in the
elimination of over 200,000 spindles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0139 </DOCNO>
