<HEADLINE> First AIDS Hospital to Be Launched in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A first specialized AIDS
hospital is to be launched in June this year, ''The New Vision''
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the hospital, which is still in
construction in Lubowa, some 30 kilometers south of Kampala, will
serve as a referral hospital and training center for nurses and
doctors in palliative care of the HIV-infected.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni first conceived the idea of
launching such a hospital during his visit to Midmay Hospital in
the United Kingdom in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The new hospital is to be initially run by the Midmay
specialists before Ugandan Ministry of Health takes it over.
</P>
<P>
Hope Kivengere, the President's press secretary, told the
paper, ''The president is open about the (AIDS) disease and will
discuss with anybody about the ways and means to fight it.''
</P>
<P>
The Midmay experts ''meet the president on regular basis to
exchange ideas and inform him of the work. This project is just a
continuation of his crusade against AIDS,'' the press secretary
added.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is one of the countries which have been hit most
seriously by AIDS in the world. An earlier report published last
December said that out of the total population of 21.5 million,
there are two million people carrying the deadly HIV virus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Has over 40% Illiteracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Among every five
Tanzanians, there are two illiterates nowadays, a newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Business Time quoted official statistics as saying that
out of the country's population which stands at about 28 million,
12 million are illiterate, of whom 7 million are girls and women.
</P>
<P>
The report said that as primary education is not compulsory in
Tanzania, about two million children of school-age are not
enrolled, only 15 percent go to secondary school and there is a
high drop-out rate among girls.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a report by the United Nations Children Fund (UNICEF)
said that Tanzania is caught in a deep crisis with its education
system which is hardly available to the poor.
</P>
<P>
"All the vital inputs from trained teachers to books, desks
and classrooms are in short supply or are missing altogether and
children's rights to education generally are not being adequately
addressed," the report said.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF said that enrollment has drooped sharply since 1980
from 93 to 69 percent and education opportunities for girls are
hampered by discrimination of various kinds.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Education Minister Juma Kapuya has said that under a
new five-year program, school enrollment is expected to rise to
85 percent, but education experts argued that such a goal is
unattainable as the whole education system is collapsing.
</P>
