<HEADLINE> HK Anti-Piracy Raid Nets 25,000 Discs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong customs officers
seized more than 25,000 pirated compact discs worth over 900,000
HK dollars (115,000 U.S. dollars) in an anti-piracy operation
Thursday, the Customs and Excise Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
During the 10-hour blitz which started at 1:30 p.m. local time,
officers raided about 10 shops at the shopping arcades on both
Hong Kong Island and the Kowloon Peninsula. Altogether 11,838
CD-ROMs, 4,251 music CDs, 9,115 video CDs and 198 game cartridges,
all of suspected infringing nature, were seized.
</P>
<P>
Protection of intellectual property rights is high on the list
of principles of the department, said a spokesman for the
department.
</P>
<P>
"We shall continue our enforcement action to combat piracy in a
bid to further protect intellectual property rights in Hong Kong,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed members of the public to provide more
information on such illegal activities by calling a 24-hour
hotline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
