<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't Warns Public Not to Eat Infected Fish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bureau of Fisheries and
Aquatic Resources Friday warned the public not to eat a species of
goby fish following reports of fish poisoning incidents in some
southeastern villages in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The fish was found to contain poisonous bacteria and not fit
for human consumption, after recent fish poisoning incidents in
the towns of Javier and Macarthur, Leyte province, which killed 10
people and seriously affected 46 others.
</P>
<P>
The fish poisoning incidents, according to bureau director
Dennis Araullo, occurred as a result of not heeding the moratorium
on the catching, transporting and marketing of the
potentially-poisonous goby fish throughout the country since 1993.
</P>
<P>
"In the process of our investigation, we learned that many of
the people in Leyte are still eating the poisonous goby fish,"
Araullo stressed in a memorandum sent to all Department of
Agriculture's regional directors.
</P>
<P>
The bureau's fish health section examined the fish samples and
found the bacteria which the fish contained could cause chronic
diseases.
</P>
<P>
In view of this finding, the Inter-Agency Committee on
Environmental Health warned that this type of fish from the Manila
Bay is also no longer fit for human consumption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
