<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Higher on Interest Rate Sentiment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Australian bond market
continued to rally Friday as market participants priced in the
greater likelihood of an interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
As offshore funds flowed into the debt market, the Australian
dollar tracked higher to close at 67.30 US cents from 66.78 at the
close Friday.
</P>
<P>
Axiom Funds Management senior economist Matthew Drennan said
the Australian dollar was in a very wide trading range at the
moment, "it's probably being pushed up on the fact that there is
some interest in the bonds from offshore, and people are just
buying up the Aussie in terms of that investment."
</P>
<P>
He said while the interest rate argument might have been
expected to push the Australian dollar lower, with offshore
investors taking positions in the domestic fixed interest market,
there was a weight of money argument which would lend support to
the currency, at least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
"If there was a rate cut in two or three months time, you'd see
the Aussie softer again," he said.
</P>
<P>
The likelihood of an interest rate cut by the third quarter of
1998 is now around 27 percent, according to an AAP survey of
financial markets economists.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 86.35 yen from 86.12 yen at
Thursday's close. It was also at 1.2282 marks from 1.2103 marks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
