<HEADLINE> S. African Deputy President to Visit Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki is to visit Japan, China and South Korea
next month to promote ties with the East Asian countries, the
Foreign Affairs Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, accompanied by Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad and
their wives, will pay the official visits from April 8 to 17, the
department said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of the visit is, among others, to inform
influential decision makers first hand of political and economic
developments in South Africa, the southern African region and
Africa in general," it said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki will also exchange ideas on multilateral issues of
common concern with the leaders, it said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki's visit to China would be the first by a South African
leader since the two countries established diplomatic ties on
January 1.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's trade with China, including that with Hong
Kong, totaled 7.7 billion Rand (1.6 billion U.S. Dollars) in
1996, 16.5 percent of the country's total trade with Asia, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said China, "the growing economic powerhouse in Asia and
the world," has investments exceeding 120 million Dollars in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The trip will also take Mbeki to Japan and South Korea, South
Africa's largest and third largest Asian trading partners and
also important investors.
</P>
<P>
Japan accounts for almost 35 percent of South Africa's trade
with Asia and has a total of 420 million Dollars of investments
in the country, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki and his wife, Zanele, would meet Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto and business leaders, and would pay a courtesy
call on the Japanese emperor and empress. 
</P>
