<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Banks Work to Boost Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Aware of the vital role exports
played in the economic development and will play in the economic
recovery, the Thai government is racking its brain to find ways to
boost exports especially through the banking system.
</P>
<P>
During the past few weeks, the central bank changed rules to
encourage commercial banks to lend a hand to exporters, who are
strapped for liquidity because the depreciation of the baht had
raised production and materials costs.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand, the country's central bank, approved last
Monday a change in capital adequacy requirement in a bid to kindle
greater enthusiasm among commercial banks to support local
exporters.
</P>
<P>
The change reduced the risk weighting of pre-shipment credits
from 100 percent to 20 percent, which means commercial banks could
maintain less capital in managing their loan portfolios.
</P>
<P>
In this way, commercial banks could increase their credit lines
to exporters while gaining more flexibility in maintaining the
capital-to-risk assets ratio within the 8.5 percent minimum.
</P>
<P>
One week later, the central bank proposed to relax the
restrictions for Bangkok international banking facilities (BIBF)
to increase cash available to local exporters.
</P>
<P>
Three changes will be made to alter BIBF operations.
</P>
<P>
First, the central bank is to reduce the minimum loan through
BIBF to exporters to 500,000 U.S. dollars from 2 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Second, BIBF is to be allowed to buy unrestricted amounts of
foreign currency-denominated export bills from local firms.
</P>
<P>
Third, BIBF will be allowed to guarantee foreign-currency debt,
including letters of credit, for local clients borrowing from Thai
commercial banks or overseas institutions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japan and the Asian Development Bank (ADB) agreed to
extend more loans to local exporters.
</P>
<P>
When visiting Thailand last Wednesday, Japanese Vice Finance
Minister Eisuke Sakakibara agreed to extend 600 million dollar
this month to help Thai exporters fund imports of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
Beside, a one billion dollar loan from international banks,
brokered by ADB, will support raw material imports and
post-shipment financing for exporters.
</P>
<P>
Thursday, President of the Export-Import (Exim) Bank of
Thailand Pridiyathorn Devakula brought another good news for
exporters, saying an additional 116 billion baht (2.6 billion
dollars) will be gradually injected into the financial system to
relieve the liquidity crunch facing cash-strapped exporters.
</P>
<P>
Besides, several measures have been taken to help exporters.
</P>
<P>
The Exim Bank directly handles three, including a one billion
baht (22 million dollars) structural adjustment loan, a 8.3
billion baht (184 million dollars) baht-denominated packing
credit, and a 13.5 billion baht (300 million dollars) loan from
Japan's Exim Bank, which is part of the loan granted by
Sakakibara.
</P>
<P>
As Exim Bank President Pridiyathorn said, these measures are
expected to give exporters a breathing space while foreign
investor confidence is restored and capital outflow is reversed.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the policy changes and the loans from outside,
some commercial banks have been reluctant to extend credit even if
borrowers are exporters.
</P>
<P>
Pridiyathorn said the current funding of 350 billion baht (7.8
billion dollars) from which banks draw to lend to exporters was
insufficient due to the fall of the baht.
</P>
<P>
Although the government projected a seven percent export growth
to 62.6 billion dollars, the Exim Bank president painted a more
gloomy picture of zero growth with a volume of about 58 billion.
</P>
<P>
He quoted the fierce competition from other exporting countries
as a result of their weakened currencies and the slackened demand
in export market such as Japan, the United States and Europe as
the reasons.
</P>
<P>
Despite the disadvantages, it is widely believed that the Thai
economy had already gone through the worst period.
</P>
<P>
So long as the banks increase capitals to meet the demand of
exporters, together with the stabilized baht, the Asian tiger will
finally emerge from the tunnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea: DPRK Soldiers Cross Military Demarcation Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen soldiers of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) crossed the military demarcation
line into the southern part of the Demilitarized Zone Thursday
morning but went back 17 minutes later, said South Korea's Joint
Chiefs of Staff Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers, who were moving along the signposts at the
demarcation line for some three kilometers and then crossed
roughly 40 meters into the southern part of the Demilitarized Zone
at 11:05 a.m. (local time) Thursday, paid no attention to the two
announcements and over 20 warning shots by the South Korean
military, said the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Chiefs of Staff did not explain why it announced the
accident a day later.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK has been in a state of wartime mobilization since
10:00 p.m. Thursday because a vital nationwide military exercise
is under way, DPRK Deputy Foreign Minister Li In Gyu said in an
emergency briefing to foreign diplomats in Pyongyang Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK stages the military exercise because it is greatly
concerned with growing foreign military threats to the country,
the deputy minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
