<HEADLINE> Beijing Set to Establish Four Economic and Trade Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua)-- Beijing, the Chinese capital,
plans to establish four foreign trade and economic cooperation
groups in 1998 as part of an effort to accelerate reform of its
foreign trade management system, according to the International
Trade News.
</P>
<P>
The four groups, which are expected to remove barriers between
different trades and promote the relocation of assets, will fall
into four categories, according to Beijing Vice-Mayor Zhang Mao.
</P>
<P>
The first category will include industrial enterprises dealing
with foreign trade. The second category represents a mixture of
enterprises from the trade, industrial, agricultural, technology
and banking sectors.
</P>
<P>
The third category will consist of a foreign economic
cooperation group mainly involving construction enterprises, which
will combine trade and banking. The fourth category consists of
pillar enterprises in the tourism and transportation sectors,
which will offer services to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The city will also explore different forms of public ownership
in the economic and trade sectors, and will accelerate the reform
of state-owned trade enterprises, said Zhang, who is in charge of
the city's economic and trade development.
</P>
<P>
Beijing registered a 1997 foreign trade volume of 15.6 billion
US dollars, up 4.6 percent on the previous year. China joined the
list of the world's top 10 trading nations with a total 1997 trade
volume of 325 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade officials have called for greater nationwide
efforts to ensure that China fulfills its 1998 target of 345
billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
