<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taxation on Foreigners in Shanghai Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners living in Shanghai
paid taxes of over 1.18 billion yuan during 1997, up 24 percent
from the previous year, according to a report released by the
city's taxation bureau.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai led all Chinese cities in terms of related tax
revenues.
</P>
<P>
The city's tax revenues have grown by an average annual rate of
40 percent over the past few years due to the rising number of
resident foreigners and strict enforcement of taxation laws and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai also levies taxes on foreign-funded firms,
representative offices and foreigners visiting the city to
participate in commercial performances and sports events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
