<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changsha Bids Adieu to Highest Flood Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The record flood peak along the
Xiangjiang River, a tributary of the Yangtze River, passed through
Changsha, capital of Central China's Hunan Province, today killing
two people and causing heavy damage to both property and
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The flood peak reached a record 37.64 meters, or 2.64 meters
above the danger level on March 10, and dropped to 35.78 meters by
early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain on March 6 caused flooding in surrounding
villages and low-lying urban courtyards. Flood waters also damaged
a number of schools and water conservancy facilities.
</P>
<P>
No major damage was reported in flooding along the Zishui
River, another Yangtze tributary.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the flooding in the middle and lower reaches
of Yangtze to the El Nino phenomenon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
