<HEADLINE> British Co. Investment in Tanzania Tops $100 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 13 (Xinhua) - The Commonwealth
Development Corporation (CDC) has invested 100 million U.S.
Dollars in Tanzania over the past 50 years to support private
sectors, said a CDC statement available here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Marking the 50th anniversary of CDC, visiting CDC Deputy
Chairman Sir William Ryrie said Thursday that his organization
will launch a joint venture capital fund with local investors to
assist Tanzania in managing and expanding its small and
medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
CDC, the Britain's overseas development financial institution
with a duty to help poorer countries by promoting private
enterprises, began its first investment in the then Tanganyika in
wattle planting in 1949, one year after its foundation.
</P>
<P>
Today, the British firm employs more than 2,500 people in
timber, wattle, tea and power production in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
It is also involved in financing gold and mineral exploration
and has played a pioneering role in the establishment of
commercial sugar production in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
"In the wake of recent increased private sector involvement in
mineral sector, CDC has made an investment stake in a new gold
mine in north Mara Region," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Early this decade, CDC demonstrated its long term commitment
in Tanzania by pioneering the concept and implementation of
commercial tea plantations in Kilombero Valley, an investment
whose first output comes after a lapse of quarter century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
