<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Leads World in Chemical Fiber Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China became the world's largest
producer of chemical fibers following a 12.4 percent growth in
output for 1997, according to the International Trade News.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper reported that the world's chemical fiber output
for 1997 hit 23.7 million tons, up 7.7 percent from the previous
year, accounting for 53 percent of the total output of various
kinds of fibers.
</P>
<P>
China also witnessed substantial growth in the production of
polyester and nylon fibers, as well as cellulose and propylene
synthetic fiber.
</P>
<P>
The world's total fiber output for 1997 hit 44.9 million tons,
up four percent from the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
