<HEADLINE> US Denies Support for Abacha Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States Thursday denied
Nigerian paper reports credited to the American ambassador to
Nigeria that he commented on the yet-to-be declared candidature
of General Sani Abacha in this year's presidential race.
</P>
<P>
It was widely reported in many Nigerian dailies Thursday that
U.S. ambassador Williams Twaddell said Wednesday that the U.S.
government would accept Abacha as the next civilian president if
it was the collective will of Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
However, Robbert Howes, director of the U.S. Information
Service (USIS) said in Abuja Thursday that the story was not
true, the Nigerian Tribune reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Howes said he had the founding after seeking to clarify the
story from Tadd Chapman, economic officer of the U.S. embassy,
who was with the envoy during a visit to Nigerian Minister of
Commerce and Tourism Emmanuel Udogu, when the reported promise
was made.
</P>
<P>
According to the USIS director, what the ambassador said at
the function was that "for the transition program to be credible,
there must be a level plain field for a free and fair election".
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the Nigerian minister has not commented or
confirmed the reported remarks, nor the U.S. ambassador. 
</P>
</TEXT>
