<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expands Tourism Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The China National Tourism
Administration (CNTA) has established 1,162 international travel
agencies as part an effort to further explore the global tourism
market.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 Category-A travel agencies formerly held CNTA approval
for booking and hosting overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
China's travel agencies were formally divided into three
categories, including Category-A operations. Category-B travel
agencies were limited to hosting overseas tourists referred by
Category-A agencies and serving domestic tourists. Category-C
travel agencies provided services for domestic tourists.
</P>
<P>
The State Council issued its Regulations on Management of
Tourism Services in October 1996, with CNTA initiating a category
adjustment program.
</P>
<P>
China currently offers two specific types of tourism agencies
-- international and domestic.
</P>
<P>
International tourism agencies have basically assumed the
business activities of the former Category-A travel agencies,
while domestic tourism agencies are limited to domestic tourism.
</P>
<P>
Tourism experts point out that the effort signals a major step
in increasing the international competitiveness of Chinese travel
agencies, and in regulating market order.
</P>
<P>
China's overseas tourism industry has witnessed annual
double-digit growth over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The country hosted a record 57.6 million overseas tourists
during Visit China '97, up 12.6 percent on the previous year, with
the sector's foreign exchange earnings hitting 12.07 billion US
dollars. The World Tourism Organization ranked China sixth
globally in accordance with related indices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
