<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Meets Palestinian Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China is fully prepared to join
the international community to advance the Middle East peace
process, according to Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister
Qian Qichen.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remarks today in a meeting with Saeb Erekat,
minister of the Local Government of the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed China's great concern about development of the
peace process in the Middle East. Qian told Erekat that China is
pleased with all progress, but is also uneasy about the current
impasse in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Qian recalled his visit to the Middle East at the end of last
year, and stressed that all countries in the region and the
international community agreed that a peaceful solution to the
Middle East issue was the only choice.
</P>
<P>
He said the Palestine issue, a major aspect of the Middle East
issue, should be resolved in a comprehensive, just and reasonable
manner. The long-standing stalemate in the peace precess will harm
both Arabs and Israelis, and will further complicate the regional
situation, said Qian.
</P>
<P>
The international community should grasp current favorable
opportunities to help all concerned parties break the impasse and
advance the peace process, said Qian.
</P>
<P>
Middle East peace talks should be based on relevant United
Nations resolutions and the principle of "land for peace", said
Qian, adding that parties concerned should abide by all agreements
and adopt a realistic and flexible attitude to realize regional
peace through dialog.
</P>
<P>
Qian said China will continue to support the just struggle of
the Palestinian people and their effort to regain occupied
territory and restore legitimate national rights.
</P>
<P>
Erekat forwarded a letter in which PNA President Yasser Arafat
briefed Chinese President Jiang Zemin on developments in the
Middle East situation.
</P>
<P>
He said Palestinians will never forget the support the Chinese
people have exhibited for their just cause, and added that his
government sincerely appreciates China's stance on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Palestine will adhere to its choice for peace and
hopes to comprehensively implement agreements reached thus far.
</P>
<P>
Erekat expressed Palestine's sincere hope that China, a
permanent member of the UN Security Council, will continue its
extensive efforts to promote the peace process and ensure a
comprehensive settlement which fully complies with the interests
of all parties in the region.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Assistant Foreign Minister Ji Peiding and Erekat met
earlier today to discuss the peace process and Sino-Palestinian
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
