<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Investigates Electromagnetic Radiation Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China is conducting a nationwide
investigation on electromagnetic radiation pollution in a bid to
tighten controls and protect public health.
</P>
<P>
An official with the National Environmental Protection Agency
(NEPA) noted that rapid economic growth has been accompanied by an
equally rapid rise in the number of facilities creating
electromagnetic radiation. He also pointed out that further
development is expected in related activities.
</P>
<P>
"Failure to properly distribute facilities will result in an
excessive concentration of power and will in turn create pollution
in surrounding areas," according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that radiation has the potential to create
long-term adverse effects on public health. Excessive radiation
disturbs normal physical functions and causes a number of diseases.
</P>
<P>
In addition, radiation disrupts telecommunications and flight
safety, according to experts. They also noted that certain signals
from radiation facilities disturb the regular operations of some
medical instruments and lead to medical accidents.
</P>
<P>
The NEPA investigation, which will be carried out over the next
year, will mainly concentrate on the nation's broadcasting and
telecommunication systems, high voltage power transmission lines
and industrial, scientific and medical facilities creating
electromagnetic radiation.
</P>
<P>
Officials point out that the investigation will provide
detailed information concerning radiation pollution and will
enable the government to strengthen related management in order to
protect the environment and public health.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing investigation is in full swing and is scheduled for
completion in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
