<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Favorable to Tanzanian Tea Growers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- While El Nino is cursed
worldwide for its damages, excessive rains brought by the weather
phenomenon has blessed tea producers in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The output of tea, a major foreign exchange earner of
Tanzania, may reach 25 million kilograms this year, up 7.9
percent over last year, Tanzania Tea Authority Marketing Director
Richard Mwakangale has said.
</P>
<P>
Tea producing regions of Mbeya, Kagera and Iringa, as well as
parts of Usambara in Tanga region, are set to record high yields,
Business Times Friday quoted the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Continuous rains and high altitude have been favorable to
producers in the areas, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Lushoto district in the northern Tanga region is the only area
where the rains have adversely affected tea production,
Mwakangale said.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains, sometimes mixed with hailstones, hinders timely
picking and transportation of the green leaf in the district to
factories for processing.
</P>
<P>
Mwakangale believes that heavy rainfall in other tea producing
areas of east Africa will equally result in bumper yields.
</P>
<P>
The expected rise in tea production, however, raises fears of
businessmen who predict auction prices in Kenya's Mombasa may
tumble. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wildlife Returning as Environment Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Jinjiang County in
southwest China's Yunnan Province have been happy to see that a
group of rhesus monkeys has found their new home in a man-made
forest. And the number of gold monkeys living in the area has
climbed to 1,200 compared with 1,000 eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
Wildlife is returning because of local people's efforts to
improve the environment by curbing soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
The county is located on the upper reaches of the Jinsha River,
a branch of the Yangtze, the country's largest river. Before the
1960s vast primitive forests were inhabited by a large variety of
wildlife such as bears, deer, leopards and boar.
</P>
<P>
Animals virtually disappeared in the decades that followed as
local people cut down trees. By the late '80s, the forest coverage
in the area had declined to less than 15
percent. Environmentalists warned that the Yangtze River area was
being turned into a second Yellow River, which is known for its
severe erosion problems.
</P>
<P>
To improve the local environment, the government has reduced
the lumbering in the area by 40 percent while encouraging local
people to plant grass and trees.
</P>
<P>
Roads and power stations have been built in the area by the
government to provide coal and electricity for local residents to
save wood. The White House Nature Reserve was set up in the area,
covering more than 190,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have paid off. The green coverage area has been
increased to 25 percent, while land erosion has dwindled to an
area of 1,000 square kilometers, about one-fourth of the previous
area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Ranks First in Consumption of Aquatic Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 13 (Xinhua)-- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, is abundant in aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
The city has kept top spot among China's major cities in per
capita consumption of aquatic products for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Guangzhou urban residents consumed 236,000
tons of aquatic products in 1997, or 60 kilograms per person.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Pearl River delta area, which is the major
supplier of aquatic products for Guangzhou, other cities and
provinces across the country also supply aquatic products for
Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Today, Guangzhou residents can enjoy imported seafood from
Australia, Norway and Thailand. Last year, about 30,000 tons of
imported aquatic products enriched residents' diets.
</P>
<P>
The abundant aquatic products and a stable market helped drive
down seafood prices from previous years. The price index in 1997
was reduced by 12 percent to that of 1996.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of consumed aquatic products in Guangzhou are
from other provinces, which made Guangzhou the distribution center
of aquatic products in south China.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou has formed 19 large aquatic products wholesale
markets. Every day, about 50 tons of quality aquatic products are
exported from Guangzhou.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
