<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 08:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negligent Father Fined in Israel, Precedence Set </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- In an unprecedented decision,
the Tel Aviv District Court has ordered a man to pay about
260,000 U.S. dollars to his three children for neglecting them, a
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The English daily The Jerusalem Post reported that Judge Henia
Stein ordered the man, Yithzak Amin, to make the payment of
300,000 shekels (86,000 dollars) to each of his three children -
two sons and a daughter who are all in their 30s now.
</P>
<P>
The judge said the fine was imposed because Amin was found to
have neglected his children and failed to provide for their
physical and emotional needs while they were growing up.
</P>
<P>
He ruled that due to the father's failure to fulfill his
paternal obligations under the law, permanent emotional damages
were caused to the children who are therefore entitled to
compensation.
</P>
<P>
This was the first court ruling establishing that a father's
legal obligations include providing love and warmth, and not just
material support. The complainants claimed that after their mother
committed suicide when they were very young, their father
remarried and basically abandoned them.
</P>
<P>
The three grew up in various institutions and stayed with
foster families until they reached majority. They described how
often their father did not let them into his house when they
wanted to come to visit him during vacations, and they were
forced to spend the nights in public parks.
</P>
<P>
Judge Stein had consulted with Attorney-General Elyakim
Rubinstein on the matter, and he said there was no reason to
block a claim for damages by children against their parents, if
they are claiming the parents had not acted in good faith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
