<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Exports Could Face Difficulties in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China's export markets could be a
problem area for the economy in 1998, today's International
Business Daily said.
</P>
<P>
The general gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate of
Southeast Asia is expected to drop to 2 percent this year from
last year's 4.5 percent, and reduce the region's import needs by
10-to-25 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The reduction was expected to decrease exports from China,
which depends on East Asia for 55 percent of its total exports.
</P>
<P>
The expanded trade deficit and aggravation of current accounts
jointly have caused East Asian nations to take measures to protect
imports such as licensing, import quotas and anti-dumping
restrictions. These measures are expected to restrain China's
exports, it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the growth
rate of the global economy will drop to 3.5 percent this
year. That of developed countries with a market economy will fall
2.5 percent. Those countries could reduce their imports from China.
</P>
<P>
An IMF analysis shows that exports from nations undergoing a
financial crisis should expand about 20 percent. Western countries
are expected to turn to those nations rather than China.
</P>
<P>
However, there are also favorable situations for China, as the
European Union further relaxed restriction against imports from
China.
</P>
<P>
China has also reached agreements with some nations after
negotiations on China's World Trade Organization membership.
</P>
<P>
And overseas investments in China continue rising, which should
helpful to China's export situation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Witnesses More Taiwanese Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province attracted 524 Taiwan-funded enterprises in 1997, with
total contractual investments standing at 610 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Up to date, Guangdong has approved over 8,900 Taiwan-funded
enterprises involving total contractual investments of 11.48
billion US dollars, accounting for one third of the nation's
total, according to a provincial official.
</P>
<P>
The official pointed out that the scope of the Taiwan
investments ranges from petrochemicals and textiles to
bioengineering and computers. The first 100 large Taiwan
enterprises entering Guangdong established 54 projects involving
an investment of over 30 million US dollars each.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan investments are currently concentrated in bonded zones
with complete equipment and favorable investment environments. In
addition, cities such as Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Shantou, Huizhou and
Dongguan have opened special development zones for Taiwan
investors.
</P>
<P>
Various areas in Guangdong have established special trade bases
for Taiwan-funded enterprises such as the high-yield agricultural
base in Dongguan, electronics-manufacturing base in Zhongshan, and
footwear manufacturing base in Nanhai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
