<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0730 GMT, March 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States hailed China's decision
Thursday to sign the International Covenant On Civil and Political
Rights, calling it a "positive and constructive step forward."
</P>
<P>
Both the White House and the State Department expressed
"welcome" to the measure announced hours earlier by Chinese Vice
Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen in Beijing. Qian told a
press conference that his country intends to sign the covenant to
show its sincerity in dealing with the human rights issue.
(US-China)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Thursday it is considering
new steps to stop the Kosovo conflict spreading to the rest of the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said that the steps
include aid to Yugoslavia's neighboring countries and increasing
the military force in Macedonia. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott will fly to the area next week for talks with leaders of
Albania, Bulgaria, Romania, Macedonia and Slovenia. The U.S. is
also considering to extend the monitoring force of 700 American
and Scandinavian soldiers in Macedonia beyond a scheduled
withdrawal at the end of August, Rubin said. (US-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
on Friday announced that the country has entered into a state of
wartime mobilization since Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
In an emergency briefing to foreign diplomats here Friday
morning, Deputy Foreign Minister Li In Gyu said that the whole
country has been in a state of wartime mobilization since 10
p.m. Thursday because an important nation-wide war exercise is
under way. Li, who accused the United States, Japan and South
Korea of making use of the DPRK's economic difficulties caused by
natural disasters, said the exercise was staged because the DPRK
was "greatly concerned" with growing foreign military threats to
the country. (DPRK-Wartime Mobilization)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) started a
naval exercise Thursday in Gaeta, 100 kilometres south of Italian
capital Rome, the Italian government announced.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, known as Dynamic Response '98, was intended to
improve coordination of multinational intervention forces and for
training military personnel from non-NATO countries. The official
said the two-stage exercise will last nine days and finish on
March 20. (Italy-Exercise)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) will soon send
a team to Jakarta to hold fresh talks with the Indonesian
government, an official said here late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chairman of the Economic and Financial Resilience
Council (DPKEK) Fuad Bawazier said the IMF team will arrive here
soon after the announcement of the new cabinet slated for tomorrow
(March 14). Meanwhile, an IMF source in Jakarta confirmed Friday
that the imminent arrival here of an IMF team which would be
headed by one of the institution's senior executives.
(Indonesia-IMF) 
</P>
