<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices in Tokyo rose sharply
Friday, buoyed by a news report that the government will infuse
1.3 trillion yen (about 10.3 billion U.S. dollars) in public funds
to push up the key Nikkei index to the 18,000 line by the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 484.92 points, or by 2.93
percent, from Thursday's close at 17,060.14.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, surged 26.49 points, or 2.12 percent,
to 1,276.20.
</P>
<P>
First Section volume increased to an estimated 770 million
shares from Thursday's 419.69 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Friday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
A daily newspaper reported Friday that the government and the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party plan to inject public money from
postal savings and postal insurance funds to push the key index to
the 18,000 mark.
</P>
<P>
Investors reacted positively to the news report and actively
purchased futures issues, prompting cash-stock buying, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,330 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outnumbered losers 1,010 to 169 with 94 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
