<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt to Listen to Views on Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government is
prepared to accept any constructive suggestions from anyone on
the land acquisition and redistribution program, a cabinet
minister has said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Thursday night, Chairman of National
Land Acquisition Committee Joseph Msika, also Minister Without
Portfolio in the office of the president and the cabinet, said
there was no going back on the land issue as the policy had been
formulated and adopted during the liberation struggle.
</P>
<P>
According to "The Herald" daily Friday, the minister was
responding to representatives of the private sector and the
Commercial Farmers' Union (CFU) at a meeting they requested on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
The private sector had requested the meeting with a view to
making a more meaningful contribution to the land reform program
through the establishment of more dialogue with the government.
</P>
<P>
Msika assured the representatives that the program had no
intention of disrupting the agricultural industry.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, the government intended to strengthen the
industry in a way that would increase productivity in both
communal and commercial farming areas.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the land acquisition program would instead
bring peace and security in the country which were a requirement
for national development.
</P>
<P>
He allayed some fears by the CFU on the criteria used by the
government in identifying land for acquisition by clearly
explaining the process.
</P>
<P>
Late last year, the Zimbabwean government announced to acquire
about 1,500 farms or five million hectares of land to resettle
landless Zimbabweans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
