<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Releases January Tourism Figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China hosted 5.08 million
overseas tourists in January this year, up 23.8 percent on the
1997 period, according to the China National Tourism
Administration (CNTA).
</P>
<P>
CNTA estimates that final figures for foreign exchange earnings
from overseas tourism will hit 920 million US dollars, up 10.7
percent on January 1997.
</P>
<P>
Spring Festival, a traditional Chinese holiday which fell on
January 28, provided a substantial increase in the number of Hong
Kong and Macao compatriots visiting inland areas, with the actual
figure rising by 30 percent to 4.46 million.
</P>
<P>
However, the sector witnessed a decline in the number of
foreign tourists. While Japan is normally China's largest source
of tourists, the number of Japanese visiting the country in
January fell by 14.8 percent to only 91,000.
</P>
<P>
Tourists from Hong Kong and Macao spent a total of 450 million
US dollars during the month, up 31 percent, with revenues from
foreign tourists dropping by eight percent to 310 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
China has initiated the '98 China Country and City Tour to
attract more overseas visitors. The major campaign offers tour
itineraries to major scenic sites in historical and cultural
cities, as well as rural scenery and folklore. Visitors can also
personally witness the changing face of China since the
introduction of the reform and opening policies in 1979.
</P>
<P>
China hosted 57.6 million overseas tourists during Visit
China '97, with foreign exchange earnings resulting from the
campaign standing at 12.07 billion US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
