<HEADLINE> UNGA President Hold Talks with Malaysian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 13 (Xinhua) -- United Nations General
Assembly (UNGA) President Hennadiy Udovenko held talks here Friday
with Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi on a number
of issues including U.N. reforms and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"The issues we discussed included Security Council reforms, the
financial problems faced by the U.N. and the current situation in
Kosovo," Abdullah told a news conference after the talks.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia was committed to the reforms within the U.N.
However, he regretted that not much progress has been made on the
U.N. reforms as too many countries have their own agenda, which
made it difficult to reach one particular formula.
</P>
<P>
He said there should be more efforts to be made to reform the
U.N. Security Council. The present arrangements are not
satisfactory, he added.
</P>
<P>
On Kosovo, Abdullah said the Kosovo crisis may be an internal
matter, but it is also an issue of human rights and the violence
in Kosovo can also affect the stability in that region.
</P>
<P>
"Because of that, the international community should not only
express concerns, but should make efforts for a proper solution,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said Malaysia welcomes the initiatives
taken by some European countries in defusing the tension in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said he and Udovenko also discussed bilateral
cooperation in various fields between Malaysia and Ukraine as
Udovenko came here in two capacities both as the UNGA president
and as Ukraine's foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko arrived here Thursday night for a three-day visit to
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko, who succeeded Malaysia's Razali Ismail as the UNGA
president, is scheduled to call on Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad and Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim before he
leaves for Tokyo Saturday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
