<HEADLINE> Presidium of NPC Session Holds Third Meeting (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Presidium of the ongoing
First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC),
China's top legislature, held its third meeting this morning.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was presided over by Li Peng, an executive chairman
of the Presidium.
</P>
<P>
The meeting approved draft resolutions on the government work
report, on implementation of the 1997 plan for national economic
and social development and a draft plan for 1998, and on
implementation of the central and local budgets for 1997 and draft
budgets for 1998.
</P>
<P>
All the three draft resolutions will be printed and distributed
to the delegations to the NPC for examination, and will be
submitted to a full meeting for final approval.
</P>
<P>
The meeting endorsed a report by the NPC Financial and Economic
Committee on its examination of the implementation of China's 1997
development plan and budgets.
</P>
<P>
The Financial and Economic Committee says in its report that
goals of China's national economic and social development for 1997
have been basically attained, with the national economy displaying
a momentum of high growth and low inflation and the macroeconomic
environment further improved.
</P>
<P>
"The guidelines, principles and emphases of the draft plan for
national economic and social development in 1998 are correct, and
the overall arrangements are basically feasible," the committee
says.
</P>
<P>
It suggests the current NPC session approve the draft 1998 plan
for national economic and social development submitted by the
State Council, and a relevant report made by Chen Jinhua, minister
in charge of the State Planning Commission, at the session on
behalf of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
The committee holds that China faces arduous tasks in promoting
economic restructuring and growth in 1998, but an annual economic
growth of eight percent is both necessary and attainable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidium of NPC Session Holds Third Meeting (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The report goes on to say that China achieved new progress in
its financial work in 1997 as a result of the deepening of reforms
and a rapid national economic growth.
</P>
<P>
It notes that last year the national fiscal revenue surged by
16.7 percent over the previous year, and the proportion of fiscal
revenue in the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) rose to 11.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The general situation for the implementation of the 1997
budgets was good," the report says.
</P>
<P>
The Financial and Economic Committee says that the 1998 draft
budgets are basically feasible, and that measures to be taken in
implementing this year's budgets are also appropriate.
</P>
<P>
It suggests the NPC session approve the 1998 draft budgets
submitted by the State Council, as well as a relevant report by
Finance Minister Liu Zhongli on behalf of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
It also suggests that the central government continue to
implement its relatively tight fiscal and monetary policy, make
every effort to reduce expenditures and fiscal deficits, and
further raise the proportion of fiscal revenue in the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting also approved draft lists of candidates for the
posts of chairman, vice-chairmen, secretary-general and members of
the Ninth NPC Standing Committee, President and Vice President of
the country, chairman of the Central Military Commission,
president of the Supreme People's Court, and procurator-general of
the Supreme People's Procuratorate.
</P>
<P>
Hu Jintao, another executive chairman of the Presidium, made
explanations on the lists, which will be submitted to NPC
delegations for further discussions as nominations by the
Presidium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
