<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province to Grow Maize in Paddy Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province,
one of the country's major rice producers, has begun developing
maize in paddy fields as part of an effort to improve agricultural
structure.
</P>
<P>
The province produced more than 25 billion kilograms of grain
in 1997, but faced serious fodder shortage when it intensified
efforts to promote animal husbandry at the same time. The province
had to ship in billions of yuan worth in maize and other fodder
crops to make up the feed shortage.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government decided to grow high-yield and
high-efficiency crops on 300,000 hectares of paddy fields
beginning this year, including 70,000 hectares of maize, according
to the province's Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
Hunan will select 30 paddy-field pilot areas to develop maize,
in a bid to have 200,000-to-300,000 hectares of quality maize
within three-to-five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
