<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Population Reaches 18.588 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia's population grew 1.2
percent in the 12 months to September 30 last year to a total of
18,588,600, the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said here on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
That was a 0.1 percent drop from the 1.3 percent growth rate of
the previous 12 months.
</P>
<P>
There were 251,800 new births, up from 250,800 the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
The natural increase, the change in the population resulting
from births and deaths, was 124,000, up 2 percent than the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
But overall population growth was slowed by a 5 percent drop in
net migration from 103,200 in 1996 to 97,900 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The number of permanent and long-term arrivals decreased by 0.5
percent and there was an 11 percent increase in the number of
people leaving for good.
</P>
<P>
The Australian federal government has cut its annual
immigration quotas during the past two years by a total of 12,000.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Considers New Steps on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Thursday it is considering new steps to stop the Kosovo conflict
spreading to the rest of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said that the steps
include aid to Yugoslavia's neighboring countries and increasing
the military force in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott will fly to the area
next week for talks with leaders of Albania, Bulgaria, Romania,
Macedonia and Slovenia, said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said also under consideration is extending the monitoring
force of 700 American and Scandinavian soldiers in Macedonia
beyond a scheduled withdrawal at the end of August.
</P>
<P>
"This is something that's under discussion right now. But yes,
we are looking at what the right mix of capabilities and missions
will best serve a situation that has gotten worse, not gotten
better."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. last week scrapped the measures to soften the
sanctions against Belgrade after dozens of ethnic Albanians died
in a Yugoslavian government crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
that he was going to ask the U.N. Security Council to review the
earlier decision to withdraw the peacekeeping force from Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly are pleased that the secretary-general agrees
with us that there is a need to have a stabilizing international
presence, a peacekeeping presence in the region," said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the troops in Macedonia is expected to expire at
the end of August this year and the Security Council decided to
pull them out by the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Rubin confirmed that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and Annan also discussed the issue and believed the troops will
remain in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We do think it's encouraging and important that the
international community is getting behind the idea that if the
current trends don't reverse themselves...one of the grave risks
here is that the violence in Kosovo will spread to neighboring
countries like the former Yugoslavian republic of Macedonia,"
Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0247 </DOCNO>
