<HEADLINE> China Setting Up Direct Channels with International Retailers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China is creating direct trade
channels with international retailers instead of the routine
contacts through intermediate business agents, according to
sources with China's Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is encouraging China's foreign trade companies to
make direct relationships with international retailers as part of
the effort to alleviate the impact of the Southeast Asian
financial crisis on China's exports.
</P>
<P>
At an international export commodity fair this week in Tianjin,
a municipality in north China, a number of purchasing agents
representing big international retail firms replaced overseas
intermediate business agents to become the fair's major
customers. Such companies include Makro from the Netherlands,
Daiei from Japan, the China Resources Holding Co. Ltd. and the
Wing On Co. Ltd. from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Carrefour Group from France gave a presentation at the fair
to hundreds of Chinese exporters on how to enter its global
purchasing network.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of the company's Asian purchases were from
Chinese markets in recent years, with 1 billion yuan worth of
commodities last year primarily household necessities, electrical
appliances, stationery, textiles and electronics, said
J.C. Goarin, Garrefour's China manager.
</P>
<P>
The store has set up 270 chain supermarkets in 14 countries and
regions including those in Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
