<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Tropical Cyclones Sweep Over Bangladesh: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Some 95 percent of the world's
tropical cyclones sweep over Bangladesh, bringing heavy loss of
life and property to this South Asian nation, a weather expert has
said.
</P>
<P>
Forty to 50 percent of disasters in country come from tropical
cyclones, M.H. Khan Chowdhury, former Meteorological Office chief,
told a workshop here on Thursday, press reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Of the cyclones formed in the Bay of Bengal during April and
May, 80 percent will surely hit the country as they have no other
tracks to divert their course," the expert said.
</P>
<P>
And cyclones during October and November that move west to
northwest lash at Bangladesh, India and Sri Lanka if they do not
recurve.
</P>
<P>
In the 22-year period between 1964 and 1986, cyclones killed
some 400,000 in the country, while the 1970 devastating cyclones
alone claimed some 300,000 lives, according to Chowdhury.
</P>
<P>
Some 138,000 Bangladeshis lost their lives in the April 29,
1991 disastrous cyclone with a wind speed of as high as 205
kilometers per hour, causing 2.4 billion U.S. dollars in material
loss to the country, the meteorological expert said.
</P>
<P>
But there was less loss of life and property in the 1997 storm
due to massive pre-disaster preparedness ahead of the disaster, he
said.
</P>
<P>
To minimize losses, an effective disaster-warning system should
be set up to disseminate disaster-warning signals quickly to the
media and agencies concerned so that immediate actions could be
taken to avert catastrophe, the expert added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Declares State of Wartime Mobilization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) on Friday announced that the country has
entered into a state of wartime mobilization since Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
In an emergency briefing to foreign diplomats here Friday
morning, Deputy Foreign Minister Li In Gyu said that the whole
country has been in a state of wartime mobilization since 10
p.m. Thursday because an important nation-wide war exercise
is under way.
</P>
<P>
Li said the exercise was staged because the DPRK was "greatly
concerned" with growing foreign military threats to the country.
</P>
<P>
He accused the United States, Japan and South Korea of making
use of the DPRK's economic difficulties caused by natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
He added that these countries are posing greater threats to the
DPRK by strengthening their alliance and indulging in frequent and
aggressive military maneuvers directed at DPRK.  
</P>
</TEXT>
