<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early Establishment of Preparatory Committee for Macao Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official in
charge of Hong Kong and Macao affairs said here today that it is
better to establish a preparatory committee for the Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR) earlier than later.
</P>
<P>
The preparatory committee should have a wide representation of
people in Macao, said Chen Ziying, deputy director of the Hong
Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council, who is
attending an ongoing session of the Ninth National People's
Congress (NPC) as a deputy.
</P>
<P>
Also, he said, the preparatory committee should have more
members from Macao than those from the mainland since the future
Macao SAR will implement the principles of "one country, two
systems" and "Macao people governing Macao" and a high degree of
autonomy for Macao.
</P>
<P>
The major task of the preparatory committee is to make
preparations for the establishment of the Macao SAR and formulate
methods for the formation of the first government of the Macao SAR
and its judicial organs, he said.
</P>
<P>
The actual date for the establishment of the preparatory
committee will be decided by the NPC and its Standing Committee in
accordance with law, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chen described the return of Macao to the embrace of the
motherland as another milestone in the great cause of
reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The "one country, two systems" policy put forward by Deng
Xiaoping has become reality in Hong Kong, he said. It not only
ensures Hong Kong's economic prosperity and social stability but
also plays a positive role in the return of Macao to the embrace
of the motherland and the settlement of the Taiwan Issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The year of 1999 will bring China a double happiness -- the
return of Macao to China, which falls on December 20, and the 50th
anniversary for the founding of new China," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have full confidence in a smooth transfer of power in
Macao," he added.
</P>
<P>
In implementing the principle of "one country, two systems,"
Macao's political, economic, historical, cultural and social
characteristics will be taken into full consideration, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
China will unite all people that can be united in Macao,
including Portuguese born in Macao, for achieving a smooth
transition and Macao's sustained economic development and social
stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chen enumerated a long list of items of work that need to be
done during the latter half of Macao's transitional period.
</P>
<P>
"It is high time that we began work on these items," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Government Decides Major Price Hikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- After heated debates, the Czech
government decided Thursday to implement major hikes in rent as
well as in the price of electricity and gas.
</P>
<P>
Beginning from July 1, rents and gas prices will rise by 27
percent while electricity will increase by 24 percent, the CTK
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the effort made by the Czech government in
the transition towards establishing a market economy. It is aimed
at correcting the low cost of rents, gas and electricity which has
incurred losses in these sectors.
</P>
<P>
The government also increased subsidies to low-income families
and pensions to the retired to offset the effects of price hikes
on those most vulnerable to price fluctuations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
