<HEADLINE> NATO not Consider Sending Troops to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- NATO has not considered sending
troops to Kosovo, Secretary-General Javier Solana reaffirmed
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Solana, who arrived in the Albanian capital, Tirana, for talks
with Prime Minister Fatos Nano, said NATO hoped diplomatic efforts
of the international community would improve the situation.
</P>
<P>
He added that Yugoslavian president Slobodan Milosovic should
find a political solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
NATO agreed to give Albania military aid at a meeting in
Brussels on Wednesday, but refused a request to send troops to the
southern boundary of Albania which borders Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that NATO appreciated Albanian efforts at
containing the conflict and his talks with Nano would further
promote bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Nano said both he and Solana decided to strengthen the
preparation work for the NATO-Albanian partnership. 
</P>
