<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. General: Crew to Blame for Cable Car Tragedy in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 12 (Xinhua) -- A United States general said
Wednesday that the four-man crew of a U.S. Marine Corps plane was
to blame for last month's cable car tragedy in Italy's Dolomites.
</P>
<P>
"It was a crew error. The crew flew lower and faster than
authorized whenever ... there was a valley," Major General Michael
DeLong said.
</P>
<P>
"The crew piloted the plane in an aggressive way, exceeding
speed limits and flying well below the set limit."
</P>
<P>
The general said that supervision and training of the crew was
also to blame because they were instructed to fly at 1,000 feet
(300 metres) rather than the 2,000 feet laid down for the region.
</P>
<P>
"We know from sources that they were flying below 1,000 feet
and hit the cables at between 366 and 373 feet. However most of
the low level portion of the flight should have been planned,
briefed and flown at 2,000 feet," said the general.
</P>
<P>
He said that the crew of the jet would now go before a
U.S. grand jury, which would decide whether they should face a
court martial.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy happened on February 3, when a low-flying
surveillance jet based at Aviano sliced through the ski-lift
cables on Mount Cormis during a training flight, sending 20 people
inside a cable car to their deaths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
