<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Tea Export Earnings up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's major traditional
export earner tea has recorded an impressive earning of 700
million U.S. dollars in 1997 up from 562 million U.S. dollars the
previous year, showing a 24.6 percent growth, according to the
Daily News Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tea earnings have outstripped other traditional export earners
rubber and coconut, Tea Board sources told the paper Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, earnings may not be as high as the impact of El-Nino
is expected to severely affect the tea plantations.
</P>
<P>
However, the Tea Research Institute has issued guidelines to
the plantations on how to minimize the damage from the El-Nino
threat, the sources was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kenya which is Sri Lanka's main competitor suffered a severe
drought last year but is now recovering from the slump which
helped Sri Lanka's tea exports increase.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has received larger orders from the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS). In addition, its exports to Turkey,
Iran, Iraq, UK, UAE, Egypt Syriya and Jordan also increased.
</P>
</TEXT>
