<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Expert on Tropical Cyclones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Some 95 percent of the world's
tropical cyclones sweep over Bangladesh, causing heavy losses of
lives and properties to the south Asian country, a weather expert
has said.
</P>
<P>
Forty to 50 percent of disasters in the country were caused by
tropical cyclones, M.H. Khan Chowdhury, former Meteorological
Office chief, told a workshop here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Of the cyclones formed in the Bay of Bengal during April and
May, 80 percent will surely hit the country as they have no other
tracks to divert their course," the expert said.
</P>
<P>
In the 22-year period between 1964 and 1986, cyclones killed
some 400,000 people in the country, while the 1970 devastating
cyclones alone claimed some 300,000 lives, according to Chowdhury.
</P>
<P>
Some 138,000 Bangladeshis lost their lives in the 1991
disastrous cyclone with a wind speed of 205 kilometers per hour,
which also caused 2.4 billion U.S. dollars losses in materials,
