<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenhouse Fruit Selling Well in Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- In early March, when cherries
produced in greenhouses in Shandong Province were ripe, they were
immediately snapped up by traders at 15 yuan (1.8 U.S. dollars)
per kilogram, 10 times the price for ordinary cherries.
</P>
<P>
East China's Shandong province, a pace-setter in growing fruit in
greenhouses, accounts for half of the 16,000 hectares of
greenhouses in the country.
</P>
<P>
While there has been an oversupply of ordinary fruit, the
supply of greenhouse fruit still falls short of demand, though the
latter is priced much higher. "This is because greenhouse products
are always available in the off-season," one market analyst said.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Yongshun, a farmer in Tengzhou in Shandong, could not sell
the cherries he grew last year and could only watch them rot. So
he decided to shift to greenhouse cherries, which earned him more
than 30,000 yuan in March.
</P>
<P>
Currently, many farmers in Shandong are growing cherries,
grapes, strawberries and plums in greenhouses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Hails China's Decision to Sign Covenant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States hailed
China's decision Thursday to sign the International Covenant On
Civil and Political Rights, calling it a "positive and
constructive step forward."
</P>
<P>
Both the White House and the State Department expressed
"welcome" to the measure announced hours earlier by Chinese Vice
Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Qian told a press conference that his country intends to sign
the covenant to show its sincerity in dealing with the human
rights issue.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Michael McCurry commented at a press
Briefing: ``Obviously the United States government welcomes
today's decision by the Chinese government as a positive and
constructive step forward.
</P>
<P>
``This decision by China to sign the covenant will represent a
formal commitment to the principles that are espoused in the
covenant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about possible impact on U.S. moves at the upcoming U.N.
Human Rights meeting in Geneva, McCurry said that Qian's
``significant'' announcement ``will be taken into account.''
</P>
<P>
However, he did not clarify if Washington had decided to drop
the sponsoring of an anti-China resolution in Geneva later this
month.
</P>
<P>
For years, the United States has tried and failed to sponsor a
resolution critical of China's human rights condition. The
prospect this year for such a document seems dimmer since
U.S. allies in Europe have decided to curtail their efforts.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin also commended the
Chinese decision, believing the Chinese government means what it
says.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen a pattern of Chinese announcements in this area,
where they first say they're going --they intend to sign a treaty
or a convention, and then they sign a treaty or a convention, and
then they ratify a treaty or convention," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Both McCurry and Rubin confirmed that President Bill Clinton
might move the date up for his trip to China.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Clinton might visit China in late June or
early July instead of November. Neither McCurry nor Rubin were
prepared to be more specific about the schedule.
</P>
<P>
"The president has a number of reasons to think about the
scheduling of the China trip. Clearly, we want to keep momentum in
this relationship: that has been progressing because of the
exchange of high-level leaders and delegations, including the
summit meetings between the two presidents," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin of China visited the United States in
late October and early November last year. He and President
Clinton agreed to establish a constructive strategic partnership
between the two countries for the next century. The two leaders
met again in Vancouver, Canada, at an APEC meeting some three
weeks later.
</P>
<P>
"I think the president has already, in a sense, assessed the
importance of the continuing dialogue he has with the highest
levels of the People's Republic leadership," McCurry said. He
described the ties with China as "one of the most important
relationships the United States has on Earth."
</P>
<P>
He said that China and the United States have cooperated well
on regional security issues, the Korean peninsula and the
four-party talks, adding that the role played by China has been
"very, very helpful."
</P>
<P>
"The president looks forward to continuing that type of
detailed, concrete dialogue with President Jiang Zemin, and I
think he hopes that this will be an occasion that we can continue
to make progress on the issues that are central to what is a very
expansive bilateral relationship," McCurry noted.
</P>
<P>
Despite the progress and improvement of the Sino-American
relationship, both China and the United States believe that more
efforts are needed to narrow their differences on the Taiwan
issue, the human rights problem and trade imbalance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
