<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto on New Government's Top Priority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
emphasized that restoring currency stability will be the most
immediate priority of the new government.
</P>
<P>
"We're not asking for much. We just want to have a stable
rupiah as that people's living standards do not fall further," the
president said here Thursday night when meeting with members of
the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), official Antara news
agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
If this was achieved, the country's economic wheels could start
rolling again, he said.
</P>
<P>
The value of the Indonesian rupiah has lost about 80 percent
against the U.S. dollar in the past eight months since the
monetary crisis, which hit most of the Southeast Asian countries
and some East Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The crisis, Soeharto admitted, had made it seem that the fruits
of the 30 years of development had been destroyed. "This crisis
has inflicted big losses on everyone," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government along with the people had made concerted
efforts to ensure adequate supply of basic commodities and
medicines.
</P>
<P>
"But the results of our efforts are still inadequate. Many
things remain to be done to restore normalcy in the situation," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, who was reelected to his seventh term of presidency
on Tuesday at the general session of MPR, is reportedly to form
his Seventh Development Cabinet on Saturday (March 14). 
</P>
</TEXT>
