<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Parliament Adopts Law on Abandoned Houses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian parliament adopted a
law on Thursday designed to invalidate war-time decisions on
abandoned houses. The new law will pave the way for an early
return of refugees who fled their homeland during years of ethnic
conflicts in the former Yugoslavian republic.
</P>
<P>
Under a war-time law on houses, owners automatically lost their
rights of residence if the houses were abandoned for more than six
months.
</P>
<P>
The war-time law on houses later became a major obstacle for
refugees returning to their homeland because they could not
re-claim their houses, which were being occupied by others.
</P>
<P>
According to the new law, previous owners of houses must
register with local authorities to claim their former properties
within six months after the law becomes effective. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
