<HEADLINE> Sweden, S.Lanka Sign Agreement on Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Sweden will contribute 15 million
U.S. dollars to a three-year agreement it has signed with Sri
Lanka on development projects in the South Asian country, the
Daily News reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used for development projects to promote
peace, democracy and economic development in the strife-torn
country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the Swedish government will provide five
million U.S. dollars a year up to the year 2000 for development
programs in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Erik Wingen, leader of the Swedish delegation which settled the
terms of the agreement, was quoted as saying here Thursday that
the development aid covered by the agreement is in addition to
contributions from sector specific funds that are considered on a
project-by-project basis and handled by the Swedish International
Development Agency.
</P>
<P>
The present ethnic conflict is identified as the greatest
obstacle to development in Sri Lanka. Sweden would try to assist
Sri Lanka in searching for a solution to the problem, Wingen told
the newspaper.  
