<HEADLINE> China's Retail Price Index Drops in First Two Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The retail price index of China
dipped 1.9 percent in February compared to the same month last
year, but commodities were 1.2 percent more expensive than
January.
</P>
<P>
A report by the State Statistics Bureau said that the consumer
price index in February registered a drop of 0.1 percent from the
same month last year, and the price level was 1.5 percent higher
than January.
</P>
<P>
For the January-February period, the retail prices decreased by
1.7 percent from the same period last year, while the consumer
price index rose 0.1 percent during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Looking across China, only the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and
Qinghai Province had increases in the retail price index in the
two-month period. Inner Mongolia's retail price index rose 0.4 percent
on a yearly basis while Qinghai's rose 0.3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
