<HEADLINE> Thai Military Officers Ordered to Use Bicycle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Thai army officers and their
families will say good-bye to their cars inside the military
camps, as the army has worked out a new policy to encourage riding
bicycles to save petrol and reduce pollution, the Bangkok Post
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 bicycles will be distributed to military units
across the nation, said Deputy Army Chief-of-Staff Pattana
Phuthananont.
</P>
<P>
The bicycle campaign was promoted by the Army
Commander-in-Chief Chettha Thanajaro, who used his personal budget
to buy part of the bicycles.
</P>
<P>
General Chettha will lead a number of army officers to ride
bicycles on March 20, to encourage people to turn to bicycles for
short-distance travel, Pattana said.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, each military camp of the army is located in a
100-rai (16 hectares) plot or larger.
</P>
<P>
According to Pattana, the army can save about 400,000 baht
(about 9,000 U.S. dollars) each month due to its campaign to
encourage officers to make prudent use of tap water, power supply
and telephone. 
</P>
