<HEADLINE> Italy's Fiat Auto Company to Open New Market in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Italy's Fiat car company will invest
about two billion U.S. dollars over the next five years to open new
markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
Fiat chief executive Roberto Testore said Thursday in Turin
when he unveiled the Seicento (600) model that his company would
invest 1.95 billion dollars before 2002 to improve its global strategy.
</P>
<P>
He said in the five years, car demand in western Europe would
grow by ten percent, by three percent in North America and would fall
slightly in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Demand in emerging economies would grow by 50 percent and the
markets of the future were mainly in China, India, eastern Europe
and some Latin American countries where Fiat would build new
plants or promote sales, said Testore.
</P>
<P>
The company would also produce 15 new models, including the
Seicento and three more this year, he said.  
</P>
