<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Cautious Optimism Seen About Philippine Banking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Some analysts have expressed
cautious optimism about the Philippine banking system, the largest
victim of the financial crisis in Southeast and East Asia, while
the country has insisted it is healthy.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Central Bank governor Gabriel Singson said the
country's banking industry remained "vibrant and fundamentally
sound" despite the major stress from the financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
He said that this vibrancy was manifested in the continuous
growth of resources, higher capitalization, a wider operating
network, expanded services and manageable levels of non-performing
loans.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics released by the Central Bank showed that
as of September 1997, the total assets of the banking system stood
at 2.6 trillion pesos (about 81 billion U.S. dollars), up 22.34
percent from the end-1996 level.
</P>
<P>
With the liberalized banking and bank branching rules since
1992, the operating network of banks had expanded. By the end of
1997, there were 1,006 banking institutions with 6,185 branches or
offices in the country.
</P>
<P>
Credit quality of the banks also remained sound. As of
September 1997, non-performing loans accounted for 3.81 percent of
the total loan portfolio. The banks' exposure to the real estate
sector was only 13.7 percent, much lower than in other countries.
</P>
<P>
The banks' profitability has been sustained. Pre-tax net income
for the first nine months of 1997 rose to 38.7 billion pesos
(about 1.2 billion dollars), 16 percent up when compared with the
same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
After the break-out of the financial crisis last July, the
Central Bank also implemented a series of measures to help the
banks weather the storm.
</P>
<P>
The measures include placing a cap on real estate loans,
adjusting the overbought and oversold foreign exchange position of
the banks, introducing a 2 percent loan-loss provision and
strengthening the supervision of accounts of both banks and their
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, were cautiously optimistic about the
country's banking system. They said the data were only up to last
September when the crisis had not yet reached the worst, adding
the cracks have begun to show this year.
</P>
<P>
Early last month, the financial crisis claimed its second
victim, the Orient Bank, the smallest bank in the country, after
forcing a small bank to close last September.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the banks also showed ominous signs. For decades
their foreign exchange position has been negative, indicating that
their foreign exchange liabilities have always exceeded foreign
exchange assets.
</P>
<P>
Data as of October 1997 showed that the net foreign assets of
the banks stood at negative 19.1 billion dollars. The unfavorable
position may aggravate the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
The banks' bad loans are also growing. The banks jacked up
their lending rates to between 26 and 40 percent during the
crisis. As a result, dozens of companies failed to pay their
loans.
</P>
<P>
The "extremely high" interest rates are also killing the
economy. Before the crisis, the banks' credit growth rate always
surpassed the increase of their assets. The country's leading
bank, Metro Bank, even had a credit growth rate of 130 percent
while managing only an asset growth of about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
But in the second half of last year, the banks went to the
other extreme and became very selective in lending money to their
clients, drawing the massive protest of the business community.
</P>
<P>
Due to a spate of corporate failures, Moody's Investors
Service, a U.S.-based credit rating agency, has lowered its
outlook from "stable" to "negative" for eight Philippine banks
including Metro Bank.
</P>
<P>
The analysts said the Philippine banking sector was in a better
position than that of other countries, but its defects also showed
up in the crisis. They suggest the monetary authorities correct
the mistakes immediately to make the banking system stronger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
