<HEADLINE> IMF Team to Visit Indonesia Again for Fresh Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) will soon send a team to Jakarta to hold fresh talks with
the Indonesian government, an official said here late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chairman of the Economic and Financial Resilience
Council (DPKEK) Fuad Bawazier said the IMF team will arrive here
soon after the announcement of the new cabinet slated for tomorrow
(March 14).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an IMF source in Jakarta confirmed Friday that the
imminent arrival here of an IMF team which would be headed by one
of the institution's senior executives.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, the IMF delayed its second tranche worth 3
billion U.S. dollars assistance to Indonesia because of the
so-called lack of reforms in the country. Meanwhile, the World
Bank and the Asian Development Bank also delayed their loans to
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In October last year, the IMF agreed to provide 43 billion
rescue package for Indonesia which had been badly hit by the
monetary crisis since July. At the end of last year, Indonesia
received the IMF's first tranche of 3 billion U.S. dollars in
long-term loan.
</P>
<P>
Since early February, the Indonesian government has repeatedly
said it is preparing to set up a currency board, which would peg
the rupiah to a hard currency.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and other international monetary institutions opposed
the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
