<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Orders Illegal Workers to Leave By May 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Labor Ministry has
ordered about 800,000 illegal workers, most of them from Myanmar,
to leave Thailand by May 1 or face legal action.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Labor and Social Welfare Trairong Suwankhiri said
on Thursday that the Thai government has set aside 24 million baht
(about 550,000 U.S. dollars) to build five detention centers along
the Thai-Myanmar border by the end of April and illegal workers
will have to report to these centers before being repatriated.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will cover the illegal workers'
transportation back home.
</P>
<P>
Illegal workers who do not return home after the deadline will
face a maximum three-year jail term and/or a fine of up to 60,000
baht (1,400 dollars), said Trairong, quoted by today's Nation
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
He said employers who harbor illegal workers after the deadline
will be imprisoned for up to five years and/or face a fine of up
to 50,000 baht (1,200 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Thailand has more than a million foreign workers, of whom
280,000 are allowed to work legally on annual permits. About 80
percent of the illegal workers are from Myanmar and the rest from
Cambodia, Laos, Bangladesh, India and Pakistan, according to the
newspaper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
