<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian, EU Share Positions on Kosovo: EU Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting European Union special
envoy Anthony Lloyd said Thursday that the Bulgarian government
and EU hold similar positions on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Kosovo has reached crisis proportions," said
Lloyd at his meeting with Bulgarian Deputy Foreign Minister
Konstantin Dimitrov, the BTA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd, who is also the British minister of state for foreign
and commonwealth affairs, said that the level of violence used by
the Yugoslavian authorities in Kosovo is unacceptable and is
condemned by the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU representative mentioned the decisions taken by the
Contact Group during its meeting in London Monday, saying that the
response was decisive and rapid.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group on Former Yugoslavia reportedly proposed
imposing an arms embargo on Belgrade if it fails to politically
resolve the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd drew attention to the joint declaration issued by foreign
ministers of Bulgaria, Greece, Romania, Macedonia and Turkey
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
He said the declaration, which condemned the violence in Kosovo
and called for a political solution to the issue, is "absolutely
consistent with the statements from the Contact Group," and
"establishes an absolute unanimity of purpose between the regional
states and the Contact Group and the world community in that
context."
</P>
<P>
As to ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, the envoy said that "whilst
we support greater autonomy, that autonomy needs to be within the
existing internationally recognized boundaries of
Yugoslavia. There is no room for secession," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He also warned ethnic Albanians not to indulge in terrorism,
saying, "There can be no support from any part of the world
community for acts of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Sofia is the last leg of Lloyd's four-nation Balkan tour which
has taken him to Skopje, Tirana and Belgrade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Telephone Museum to Open in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A telephone museum, the 101st
museum in the Chinese capital, is expected to open to visitors in
May.
</P>
<P>
The museum has three exhibition halls, with a combined floor
space of nearly 800 square meters. Exhibits include more than 300
telephone sets, switchboards and other telephone-related
instruments.
</P>
<P>
Common-battery, magnet, step-by-step and program-controlled
telephones, as well as a phone used by the last emperor of the Qing
Dynasty (1644-1911), are among those on display.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's first government-run telephone bureau was established
in 1904, the bureau has a switchboard with a capacity of 100 lines.
</P>
<P>
Today, Beijing has a combined switchboard capacity of more than
3 million lines, with more than 2 million telephone subscribers,
which means 55 telephones for per 100 urban residents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 34 Ministers of American Continet to Meet Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The ministers of 34 American
countries will meet in San Jose next Thursday for fresh
negotiations on the proposed Free Trade Area of the Americas
(FTAA).
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting of preparatory talks is crucial for the
creation of the FTAA, Costa Rican Foreign Trade Minister Jose
Manuel Salazar said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will sign the "Declaration of San Jose" and an
outline of negotiations subject to the approval of the summit of
the Americas next month in Santiago, Chile, added Salazar.
</P>
<P>
The preparatory meetings have been held since the Summit of the
Americas in December 1994, when the presidents agreed to set up
the FTAA in 2005.
</P>
<P>
Some countries have proposed to mark the formal start for the
FTAA negotiations in the next summit.
</P>
<P>
Cuba is the only country excluded from the FTAA plans because
of its ideological differences with the United States.
</P>
<P>
The representatives have made some progress in the definition
of the objectives and mechanisms of negotiation, but differences
in agriculture, subsidies, measures against unfair competition,
labor and environmental matters must still be resolved.
</P>
<P>
The Southern Common Market (Mercosur) countries -- Argentina,
Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay -- want agriculture discussed in a
special table of negotiations, while the United States prefers it
in a table on access to markets.
</P>
<P>
Mexico insists subsidies and unfair competition be treated
within the theme of competition policies, but the United States
wants them dealt with separately.
</P>
<P>
Governments still face problems in reconciling the interests of
economies so different as the United States and poorer Latin
American and Caribbean countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Province to Use Overseas Funds for Key Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province
plans to attract 500 million US dollars of overseas funds this
year to fuel the construction of its key projects.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi, the country's largest coal base, plans to absorb 300
million US dollars of overseas loans and 200 million dollars of
overseas direct investment, according to officials with the
provincial planning commission.
</P>
<P>
It will borrow 140 million dollars from international financial
institutions such as the World Bank, the Asian Development Bank
and International Fund for Agricultural Development, and 70
million dollars of government loans from countries including
Australia, Italy, France, Germany, Spain and the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
These funds will be used in the province's major projects
including the construction of Yangcheng Power Plant, the expansion
of Wenxi Cement Plant and Shanxi International Trading Center.
</P>
<P>
The Yangcheng Power Plant alone, believed to be the world's
largest, is expected to use nearly 100 million US dollars this
year.
</P>
<P>
With a total investment of 13.2 billion yuan (1.59 billion US
dollars), the plant will have six 350,000-kilowatt sets with a
combined generating capacity of 2.1 million kw. 
</P>
</TEXT>
