<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Textile Sector Facing Less Export But New Hope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Though China's textile exports
are suffering losses in the Asia financial crisis, China still has
opportunities to recover through processing trade, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics reveal that because of the financial turmoil
in the region, China's textile exports have plummeted since the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
China has mapped out its strategy to offset the region's
currency difficulties by importing raw materials from other
countries and processing them into final products for sale. Other
Asian countries are doing the same thing.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based paper noted that although the exporting price
of other major Asian textile exporters is much cheaper, it will be
more expensive for them to import the raw materials because of the
price devaluation in these countries.
</P>
<P>
As for China, the prices of imported raw materials are dropping
faster than the prices of the exported processed goods.
</P>
<P>
Customs figures indicated that so far this year, the prices of
China's textile exports have dropped by five to ten percent. By
comparison, the price of China's textile imports fell by seven to
13 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government can help the manufacturers by increasing their
tax rebate and helping them find new business opportunities, said
the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina's economy grew by 8.4 percent last
year, the Economy Ministry announced.
</P>
<P>
The goods sector grew 9.7 percent and services 6.7 percent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the Argentine economy will grow eight
percent during the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Copper, the main Chilean export, increased in price
in the London Metals Exchange from 79.06 cents a pound to 80.61
cents on Wednesday, reported the Chilean Copper Commission
(Cochilco).
</P>
<P>
The average monthly price is 78.87 cents, while the annual
average is 78.62 cents.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The Venezuelan government plans to float 500 million
dollars of bonds in the U.S. market, said the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The resources obtained from the bonds will be used to pay
overdue foreign debt and to restructure the loan about to reach
maturity.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina's oil export income faces a
600 million dollar fall this year from the two billion dollar
total last year.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Lapena, president of the General Mosconi Energy
Institute, said that if the price of crude oil maintains the low
levels of February and March, between 15.5 and 16 dollars a
barrel, oil sales will drop 30 percent to 1.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean fish exports amounted to 151 million
dollars in January, a 15.3 percent drop compared to the same month
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the main buyer of frozen salmon, but sales fell 28.2
percent due to a 40.9 percent price decrease.
</P>
</TEXT>
