<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0001 GMT, March 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Lawyers for U.S. President Bill Clinton and
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky were in court Thursday
to argue before a federal judge in Washington D.C. that
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's office should be disciplined
for alleged media leaks.
</P>
<P>
David Kendall, Clinton's personal attorney David Kendall, filed
the complaint about leaks in February. He was joined by Lewinsky
attorney William Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
Leaks about confidential grand jury processes can be punished
by contempt of court citations. (BC-US-Intern)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON - The United States said on Thursday it was
considering extending mandate of the small force of
U.N. peacekeepers in Macedonia because of fears the crisis in
nearby Kosovo province could spread.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told a regular briefing
that the U.S. is considering the force of 700 American and
Scandinavian soldiers might be enlarged or given new rules of
engagement.
</P>
<P>
"This is something that's under discussion right now. But yes,
we are looking at what the right mix of capabilities and missions
will best serve a situation that has gotten worse, not gotten
better." (BC-US-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said on
Thursday that his country was recovering from a financial crisis
and expected other countries in the region to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
Chuan made the remarks at a meeting with U.S. key leaders in
the Senate and the House of Representatives, including House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, Sen. Jesse Helms, chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, and Rep. Benjamin Gilman,
chairman of the House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Thai prime minister started his visit to Washington on
Thursday. The purpose of his visit is to reduce strains in
U.S.-Thai relations as a result of what was seen in Bangkok as
Washington's slow response when the economic crisis first hit here
last Summer. (BC-US-Thai-Visit )
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said on Thursday that he had lengthy discussions on Iraq
with President Bill Clinton and his foreign policy team members.
</P>
<P>
Before winding up his two-day visit to Washington, Annan said
he had reassured the Washington about his pact, reached on Feb.
23, with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
He also repeated his warning to Iraq of real danger by failing
to honor the agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Iraq should understand that if this effort
to ensure compliance through negotiations is obstructed by evasion
or deception, as were the previous efforts, diplomacy may not have
a second chance," he said at a press conference at the National
Press Club.(BC-US-Iraq-Annan)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. trade deficit in the broadest measure of
current account jumped to 166.4 billion U.S. dollars last year,
the second worst showing on record, the Commerce Department
reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The department said the 1997 deficit in the current account,
which covers trade in merchandise, services and investments as
well as aid, increased 12.3 percent from the 1996 imbalance of
148.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 deficit is only next to a 168.1 billion dollar
all-time high set in 1987, a year when the U.S. manufacturers were
being battered by foreign competitors and the high value of the
U.S. dollar that helped imports less
expensive. (BC-US-Trade-Deficit )
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Pentagon said today that some public tours at
the Pentagon were stopped because of threats by terrorist
activities against installations of the Defense Department in the
Washington area.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Bryan Whitman said Washington's largest
federal building went on "heightened alert status" after the
Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) warned Wednesday evening of
"possible terrorist activity aimed at installations in the
National Capital Region." (BC-US-Pentagon-Tour)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- U.S. special coordinator for Cyprus, Thomas Miller
said Thursday that he had "very constructive" contacts with the
Turkish officials on the Cyprus issue, according to the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Miller, who arrived here late Wednesday, has met with Turkish
State Minister for Europe and Cyprus Sukru Sina Gurel.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Cyprus is not static. My mission is to
bridge the differences and help the parties to find opportunities
which sometimes are not very visible," he told reporters after the
meeting. (BC-Turkey-Cyprus-U.S. Envoy)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid
Thursday defended the Arab resistance to Israeli occupation of
their land as fully legitimate, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"The continued occupation of Lebanese and other Arab land will
only whet Arab resistance to that occupation. Such resistance was
invested with full legitimacy while that occupation lacked any,"
said Abdul-Meguid. (BC-AL-Lebanon-Israel)
