<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The 39th annual assembly of the
Interamerican Development Bank (IADB) was held in the Colombian
city of Cartagena de Indias and more than 4,000 delegates from
American countries attended.
</P>
<P>
Themes of unemployment, poverty, exclusion and violence are
discussed.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The First Nicaraguan International Fair will be held
March 17 to 22 in the Olof Palme Convention Center in Managua,
announced the organizers.
</P>
<P>
The fair will be attended by 120 firms from nine countries,
including 35 Nicaraguan companies, said "Ferias Internacionales"
marketing director Celia Chavarria.
</P>
<P>
The fair aims to attract investment into Nicaragua, to create
new jobs and revitalise the country's economy, said Chavarria.
</P>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA -- The European Union (EU) has expanded its fishing
support program in Central America to 18 months, said the
Honduran Agriculture and Livestock Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The program had raised the living standards of Honduran
fishermen of the Coyolito zone, in the Pacific Gulf of Fonseca.
</P>
<P>
The program supplied fishermen with equipment to catch shrimp,
shark, and other species.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican exports amounted to 353.97 million
dollars last January, a 16.68 percent increase over the same month
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Industrial exports amounted to 176.77 million dollars,
agriculture 148.98 million dollars, and livestock and fishing
28.22 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the United States in January amounted to 45.11
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
BRAZILIA -- Sales of imported motor vehicles in Brazil reached
44,555 units during the first two months of the year, a 29.54
percent drop over the same period in 1997, said the Brazilian
Association of Motor Vehicle Importing Firms. enditem



