<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Monetary Authorities Cut Banks' Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines has slashed the statutory reserve requirement of banks
to help lower interest rates, a leading newspaper revealed on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statutory reserve, a portion of total deposits which must
be kept in the central bank vault, will be cut by three percentage
points to 10 percent at the end of the month, the Manila Bulletin
quoted a statement from the bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the banks' liquidity reserves, which they are
required to invest in government securities, will be raised by
three percentage points to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The adjustment of reserve requirements is expected to
meaningfully lower bank lending rates by reducing bank
intermediation cost by at least 0.66 percent," Central Bank
Governor Gabriel Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Prime rates, offered to the banks' most creditworthy customers,
averaged 21 percent this week while the maximum, non-prime rates
were at around 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
Lending rates rose sharply last year as Philippine banks became
more cautious amid the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the liquidity reserves would also be raised
from 4 percent to 7 percent so that there would be no monetary
impact as a result of the cut in the statutory reserves, Singson
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
