<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Visits Bosnian Serb Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana expressed the hope Thursday that the Kosovo issue will not
affect the positive developments in the Serb republic of
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Bosnian Serb leaders in Banja Luka, the visiting
NATO chief expressed satisfaction with the reconstruction process
in the Bosnian Serb republic and with efforts made by Bosnian Serb
leaders to implement the Dayton peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Dayton peace agreement, or the Bosnian peace agreement, was
signed in Paris on December 14, 1995, to ensure a lasting peace in
the war-torn former Yugoslavian republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
NATO Supreme Allied Commander in Europe Wesley Clark is also
accompanying Solana on the trip.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic and Prime Minister
Milorad Dodik held separate meetings with the visiting NATO
leaders on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After the meetings, Plavsic told reporters she briefed NATO
leaders on recent reforms carried out in the interior
ministry, the justice ministry and the general staff of the Bosnian
Serb republic.
</P>
<P>
She said these crucial reforms were conducive to the
implementation of the Dayton peace agreement and the prosperity of
the Bosnian Serb republic.
</P>
<P>
Dodik said he discussed with the NATO leaders the difficulties
facing the Bosnian Serb government in striving for the recovery of
the national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
