<HEADLINE> Paraguay's President Denied Charge of Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Paraguayan President Juan
Carlos Wasmosy Thursday denied the charge of a "self-inflicted
coup" and promised to respect the results of the general elections
scheduled for May 10.
</P>
<P>
Oppositions accused Wasmosy of plotting a coup against himself
to thwart the general elections to stay in power.
</P>
<P>
The Paraguayan president warned that if constitutional order is
subverted, he would use the armed forces to defend the legally
constituted government.
</P>
<P>
The Superior Court of Electoral Justice (TSJE) rejected the
ruling Colorado Party's new list of presidential candidates
Wednesday, and said the official deadline for formally registering
presidential candidates had expired.
</P>
<P>
The Colorado Party requested Tuesday the TSJE accept its new
list of presidential candidates -- in which Raul Cubas Grau is
named as its candidate for president -- in place of the present
list that names Lino Oviedo as the presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Oviedo, former chief of the army and a retired general, was
sentenced to 10 years in prison by a special military court on the
charge of conspiring to topple Wasmosy in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Oviedo's candidacy had been challenged by President Wasmosy and
former Foreign Minister Luis Maria Argana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
