<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Province Increases Social Security Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of
employees in the capital of south China's Guangdong Province are
receiving better welfare benefits from the city.
</P>
<P>
Now, 3.74 million people have participated in social security,
with 64,000 poor households receiving aid. In 1997, employees'
per-capita monthly income exceeded 1,000 yuan, a year-on-year
increase of 12 percent, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
The city has intensified efforts to develop such social
benefits as old-age pensions, unemployment insurance, industrial
accident benefits and birth insurance. It has also set up a
minimum wage system, a bottom line for living expenses and a
subsidy standard as well as re-employment and aid-the-poor
projects.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 1.1 million people bought old-age insurance
policies, with 350,000 retirees getting 434 yuan per person each
month. More than 60 million yuan was paid to the unemployed at
430 yuan each per month.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou established a re-employment fund and raised 50
million yuan by last year, with more than 8,000 people already
benefiting. So, it was able to keep the unemployment rate below
2.5 per cent, below the national average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
