<HEADLINE> Panama, U.S. to Discuss on Drug Centre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian Foreign Minister
Ricardo Alberto Arias will travel next week to the United States
to discuss proposals for a multilateral antidrugs centre.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the minister had already had contacts with
the head of the U.S. negotiating team, Thomas McNamara, on the
legal basis of the centre.
</P>
<P>
Panama and the United States agreed last December in principle
to establish the antidrugs centre in 2000 and operate it for 12 or
more years in the U.S. Howard Air Base on the banks of the Panama
Canal.
</P>
<P>
The base will revert to Panamanian sovereignty next year, in
agreement with the Torrijos-Carter treaties, signed in 1977.
</P>
<P>
The United States would pay Panama a total of 53.5 million
dollars for the houses to be occupied by the personnel of the
multilateral antidrugs centre. 
</P>
</TEXT>
