<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gansu Province Strengthens Yellow River Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Gansu Province
has taken measures to upgrade the water quality of the Yellow
River, the second longest in China.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River rises on the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau and flows
through Lanzhou, capital of Gansu. Some 20 major sources of waste
water pollution have been found in and around the densely
populated capital.
</P>
<P>
The water quality of the Yellow River in Lanzhou has
deteriorated to a fourth-grade rating due to rapid social and
economic developments in recent years, according to the Gansu
Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Lanzhou has placed priority on the protection of potable water
resources, with a six-sq.km. area surrounding the city designated
as a first-degree protection zone. The zone prohibits construction
of any projects which might pollute the environment.
</P>
<P>
Waste water outlets in the area will either be treated or
closed within a deadline set by the local government, and
inspections will be carried out on all polluting sources in order
to ensure the quality of drinking water meets state standards.
</P>
<P>
The province will require all industrial pollution sources
along the Lanzhou section of the river to fully comply with the
discharge standards by the year 2000 in order to raise the water
quality to a third-degree state rating. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
