<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Considers New Steps on Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) - The United States said on
Thursday it was considering extending mandate of the small force
of U.N. peacekeepers in Macedonia because of fears the crisis in
nearby Kosovo province could spread.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told a regular briefing
that the U.S. is considering the force of 700 American and
Scandinavian soldiers might be enlarged or given new rules of
engagement.
</P>
<P>
"This is something that's under discussion right now. But yes,
we are looking at what the right mix of capabilities and missions
will best serve a situation that has gotten worse, not gotten
better."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. last week lifted the measures to soften the sanctions
against Belgrade after dozens died in conflict in Kosovo, accusing
the Yugoslav authorities of being responsible for the deaths.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan told reporters
that he is going to ask the U.N. Security Council to review the
earlier decision to withdraw the peacekeeping force from
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly are pleased that the secretary-general agrees with
us that there is a need to have a stabilizing international
presence, a peacekeeping presence in the region," said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
"Precisely what form that international peacekeeping presence
would take is something that one can discuss," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Mandate of the troops in Macedonia is expected to expire at the
end of August this year and the Security Council decided to pull
them out by the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Rubin confirmed that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
Annan also discussed the issue and believed the troops will remain
in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We do think it's encouraging and important that the
international community is getting behind the idea that if the
current trends don't reverse themselves...one of the grave risks
here is that the violence in Kosovo will spread to neighboring
countries like the Former Yugoslavia Republic of Macedonia," Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
That's why it's so important to ensure that all steps are
taken, including the possibility of extending the military
presence in Macedonia, the spokesman affirmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
