<HEADLINE> Washington District Courthouse Busy with Lewinsky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Lawyers for U.S. President
Bill Clinton and former White House intern Monica Lewinsky were in
court Thursday to argue before a federal judge in Washington D.C.
that independent counsel Kenneth Starr's office should be
disciplined for alleged media leaks.
</P>
<P>
David Kendall, Clinton's personal attorney David Kendall, filed
the complaint about leaks in February. He was joined by Lewinsky
attorney William Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
Leaks about confidential grand jury processes can be punished
by contempt of court citations.
</P>
<P>
Chief U.S. Judge of the district court Norma Holloway Johnson
is expected to rule on the complaint soon, although even her
ruling may be kept sealed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, White House adviser Bruce Lindsey was back before
Starr's federal grand jury investigating alleged Clinton affair
with Lewinsky and a potential cover-up.
</P>
<P>
Lindsey returned after Johnson allowed him to reserve some
testimony while the issue of whether some of his conversations
with the president were protected by executive privilege was
hashed out.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, White House steward Bayani Nelvis made his third
appearance before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
After his testimony, Nelvis did not respond to reporters'
questions. Nelvis and his lawyers also did not say whether he has
completed his testimony or expects to be called back.
</P>
<P>
In his earlier testimony, Nelvis reportedly said he never saw
the president and Lewinsky alone in the White House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
