<HEADLINE> France Buys Half of S. African Defense Electronics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- France has bought up half of a
South African defense electronics company, the Altech Defense
Systems (ADS), reported Agence France-Presse (AFP) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The French defense electronics company Thomson CSF and the
South African company Allied Technologies (Altech), which owns
ADS, signed an agreement on March 1, under which Thomson CSF
bought 50 percent of the shares of ADS with several million South
African rands, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
This is the first joint operation ever launched in South Africa
by Thomson CSF, the world's third largest defense electronics
company which has already launched joint operations with 25
companies around the world.
</P>
<P>
Both Thomson CSF and Altech will yield 10 percent of their
shares of ADS to a company owned by black South Africans in the
next few months.
</P>
<P>
ADS, which has an annual sales figure of 200 million rands
(about 27 million U.S. dollars), is specialized in developing
logistical materials and defense systems for the South African
military forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
