<HEADLINE> Chuan Says Thailand Recovering from Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai said on Thursday that his country was recovering from a
financial crisis and expected other countries in the region to
bounce back.
</P>
<P>
Chuan made the remarks at a meeting with U.S. key leaders in
the Senate and the House of Representatives, including House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, Sen. Jesse Helms, chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, and Rep. Benjamin Gilman,
chairman of the House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Thai prime minister started his visit to Washington on
Thursday. The purpose of his visit is to reduce strains in
U.S.-Thai relations as a result of what was seen in Bangkok as
Washington's slow response when the economic crisis first hit here
last Summer.
</P>
<P>
Chuan spent most of his first day in Washington meeting those
key lawmakers and he will hold talks with President Bill Clinton
and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said his country would continue to cooperate with the
International Monetary Fund, which had helped Thailand with a
$17.2 billion rescue package.
</P>
<P>
Thailand was the first Asian nation to succumb to a financial
crisis last Summer and the first to receive IMF help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
