<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy to Create One Million New Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Strong economic growth in Canada
will create more than one million new jobs during the next four
years, the Bank of Montreal predicted Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This will reduce the jobless rate to 7.5 percent by the year
2000 from the current rate of around nine percent, the bank said
in a report.
</P>
<P>
"Canada's economy will grow at an annual average rate of 3.3
percent between 1996 and 2001, more than one percentage point
faster than during 1991-96," it said.
</P>
<P>
The study looked at the prospect for production and job growth
of 44 industries through the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Growth leaders include machinery, electrical and electronic
products, communications, plastic products, transportation
equipment, pipelines and furniture.
</P>
<P>
Sectors such as primary metals, mining, forest products,
tobacco, beverages, and public services are expected to grow at a
below-average pace, the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
