<HEADLINE> Mutual Life to Buy Metlife's Canadian Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Mutual Life of Canada announced
Thursday that it is buying the Canadian operations of the New
York-based Metropolitan Life Insurance Company for 1.2 billion
dollars (840 million USD).
</P>
<P>
The deal will create the second largest individual and group
insurance company in Canada, with more than 40 billion dollars
assets under management.
</P>
<P>
"This acquisition will create long-term economic value for
policyholders and future shareholders, and solidifies our
competitive position in Canada," Mutual's president and CEO Robert
Astley said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The Metlife operation is a great fit with ours. With a larger
sales force, we can deliver even better service and an expanded
portfolio of products to Canadians."
</P>
<P>
Astley said that a prime reason for the acquisition is
Metlife's quality national sales forces of 1,150 agents and
managers.
</P>
<P>
The combined sales force will exceed 3,000, one of the largest
direct financial services sales forces in Canada.
</P>
<P>
The closing date for the deal, subject to regulatory approval,
is expected to be June 30.
</P>
<P>
On closing, Mutual will acquire over six billion dollars of
assets. Its total assets under management will approach 50 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
