<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Says to Have Assured Washington on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said on Thursday that he had lengthy discussions on Iraq
with President Bill Clinton and his foreign policy team members.
</P>
<P>
Before winding up his two-day visit to Washington, Annan said
he had reassured the Washington about his pact, reached on Feb.
23, with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
He also repeated his warning to Iraq of real danger by failing
to honor the agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Iraq should understand that if this effort
to ensure compliance through negotiations is obstructed by evasion
or deception, as were the previous efforts, diplomacy may not have
a second chance," he said at a press conference at the National
Press Club.
</P>
<P>
"No promise of peace and no policy of patience can be without
limits. It is my sincere hope that the government of Iraq does
understand this," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides Clinton, Annan also talked with National Security
Adviser Sandy Berger, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
Defense Secretary William Cohen on the issue of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton praised Annan for negotiating the agreement,
which had reduced for the moment the threat of U.S. air strikes on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement, on its own terms, preserves the integrity of
the inspections," Clinton said during his talks with Annan.
</P>
<P>
If the agreement were fulfilled, "then we would be able to do
what the United States has always wanted, which is to complete the
inspection process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Congress, however, was not happy with the agreement, arguing
that the United Nations would soften its stand against Iraq under
the accord.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said that the agreement "is clearly not a sellout."
</P>
<P>
Annan left Washington with a key difference with the Clinton
administration unresolved -- whether the United States, which has
a substantial military force arrayed in the Gulf, has the
authority to strike Iraq without further U.N. action.
</P>
<P>
Annan said Washington should first consult with the Security
Council before it decided to use force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the United States would consult the Security
Council but it need no approval of the United Nations for its
any kind of military actions against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
