<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Calls Tuesday's Shooting as Tragic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 12 (Xinhua) -- As part of efforts to repair
the political damage of Tuesday's killing of three Palestinians,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu admitted Thursday that
the incident was a "tragic mistake."
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the Arab service of Israeli state
television Channel I, Netanyahu asked the families of the
Palestinian victims to accept his condolences. He also pledged to
make efforts to push forward the peace process with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But he defended the action of the three soldiers who opened
fire at the van carrying the Palestinian workers, saying they
truly believed their lives were in danger at that time.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers said they regarded the driver of the van as trying
to launch a terror attack as he drove toward the roadblock near
Hebron and knocked down their commander.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu praised the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) for
cooperating in calming the tense situation in the territories.
</P>
<P>
Widespread clashes were triggered in the region by the killing
as outraged Palestinians threw stones and petrol bombs at Israeli
soldiers. Several dozens of Palestinians were wounded by rubber
bullets in the past three days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai Thursday
telephoned PNA President Yasser Arafat to brief him on the Israeli
investigation into the shooting incident. Mordechai promised that
the final results of the probe would be transferred to the PNA,
calling on Arafat to continue to work to calm the situation.
</P>
<P>
Expressing sorrow over the death of the Palestinians,
Mordechai added that he had ordered Israeli forces to avoid
clashing with Palestinian protesters. A day earlier, Mordechai
also phoned PNA deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) to call for
cooperation in preventing the escalation of violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
