<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Russia to Cooperate in Fighting Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Russia
will appoint mutual police attaches in a joint drive to fight
international crime syndicates in accordance with a treaty signed
Thursday in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Safety and Security Minister
Sydney Mufamadi and visiting Russian Deputy Chairman Anatoly
Kulikov, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of police attaches would streamline the
exchange of intelligence between the two countries, Kulikov said.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi said the police forces of the two countries would
cooperate closely to track international syndicates smuggling
uranium, diamonds and gold.
</P>
<P>
They would also work together in the prevention, detection,
suppression and investigation of other crimes, including murder,
money laundering, and trafficking in drugs, firearms and
radio-active material, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi said there were strong similarities in the crime
patterns of South Africa and Russia. Both were in a period of
transition and were facing new threats in the form of organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
"In both countries, a number of criminal syndicates are
operated by foreigners who ruthlessly exploit the vulnerability
of a state in transition," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Devises Cheap Method to Clear Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Defense researchers in Britain
have developed a cheap, safe and simple method of burning
landmines without having to explode them.
</P>
<P>
The firework-like device, named FireAnt, can be operated by a
battery from a distance of 50 meters, the New Scientist magazine
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It works by directing a jet of flame at landmines from a few
centimeters away, searing a hole in the casing, igniting the
detonator before it can set off the mine and incinerating the high
explosive so that it simply burns off without exploding.
</P>
<P>
FireAnt torches the mine for around 25 seconds, leaving the
explosives to burn themselves out in a few minutes, the magazine
said.
</P>
<P>
Because the flame is hot enough to burn a hole through at least
one millimeter of steel in seconds, it can deal with both metal
and plastic landmines.
</P>
<P>
Anti-tank mines, which are bigger, can be destroyed by
simultaneously directing three or four FireAnt at them.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at Britain's Defense Evaluation Research Agency,
which developed FireAnt, said that individual unit of the device
could sell for as little as 15 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations puts the cost of clearing one landmine by
the traditional method, either defusing it or blowing it up, at
300-1,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
With some 110 million landmines still uncleared around the
world, the potential savings could be massive, researchers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0342 </DOCNO>
