<HEADLINE> Egypt: No Discrimination Against Religious Minority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Minister of Economy
Youssef Boutros Ghali said Thursday that Egypt bears no
discrimination against its religious minority.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt does not have any form of discrimination, either based
on color, race or religion," Boutros Ghali told a visiting
delegation from the New York-based World Council of Churches.
</P>
<P>
"Egyptians are tolerant by nature and are far from being
fanatics," the minister said, responding to queries on social,
religious and religious affairs in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The minister also denounced various kinds of terrorist acts
which have killed dozens of Coptic Christians in southern Egypt in
1997, saying when terrorists strike all Egyptians are victims.
</P>
<P>
He also expounded the role of the Egyptian government and
religious institutions in upgrading the standard of living for all
social groups without distinction.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, the U.S. delegates discussed with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak the claims by western media on an alleged
strife between Egyptian Muslims and Christians.
</P>
<P>
The delegates, who arrived here Tuesday on a five-day visit,
met Wednesday with Grand Imam of Al Azhar Sheikh Mohammad Sayed
Tantawi and Pope Shenuda III of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been accusing Cairo of persecuting Copts, whose
6 million population constitutes a principal part of Egypt's
Christians. Muslims account for about 90 percent of the country's
62 million population.
</P>
<P>
Some Congressional members have called for the American
intervention to protect the Copts of Egypt, claiming they were
religiously persecuted. They also called for sanctions on
countries where religious minorities were subjected to any kind of
persecution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
