<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Threatened by Terrorist Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon said today that
some public tours at the Pentagon were stopped because of threats
by terrorist activities against installations of the Defense
Department in the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Bryan Whitman said Washington's largest
federal building went on "heightened alert status" after the
Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) warned Wednesday evening of
"possible terrorist activity aimed at installations in the
National Capital Region."
</P>
<P>
"We've been notified by the FBI of possible terrorist activity
in the next couple of days," said Glenn Flood, another Pentagon
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Flood said Pentagon tours that are planned in advance were
continuing but those for visitors who show up unannounced have
been canceled for Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
The heightened state of alert began about 6 p.m. Wednesday.
Under such alert, security personnel were screening passes for
those entering the building more closely and might conduct random
searches of packages and briefcases. Access to the building could
also be restricted, Whitman and Flood said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
