<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Under Current Account Shoots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit in the
broadest measure of current account jumped to 166.4 billion U.S.
dollars last year, the second worst showing on record, the
Commerce Department reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The department said the 1997 deficit in the current account,
which covers trade in merchandise, services and investments as
well as aid, increased 12.3 percent from the 1996 imbalance of
148.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 deficit is only next to a 168.1 billion dollar
all-time high set in 1987, a year when the U.S. manufacturers were
being battered by foreign competitors and the high value of the
U.S. dollar that helped imports less expensive.
</P>
<P>
Most economists are forecasting that the already high deficits
will rise even further this year as the Asian financial chaos cuts
into the U.S. exports to the region and at the same time enhances
sales of Asian products in this country.
</P>
<P>
Signs of the worsening development was seen in the final three
months of the year when the current account deficit climbed up to
a record high of 45.6 billion dollars, up 5.8 percent as against
the third quarter deficit of 43.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
For the year of 1997, the investment category registered a
deficit for the first time in the post World War II period. In
this category, the deficit of 14.3 billion dollars in the year
followed a surplus of 2.8 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Some economists forecast that the investment category will
likely continue the trend since the United States has become the
world's largest debtor country. It also could mean that foreigners
own more in U.S. assets such as stocks, bonds and real estates
than that the Americans own in foreign assets abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980313.0347 </DOCNO>
